# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bbc-news
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] A widespread famine affected Ethiopia from 1983 to 1985.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The worst famine to hit the country in a century, it affected 7.75 million people (out of Ethiopia's 38–40 million) and left approximately 300,000 to 1.2 million dead.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] 2.5 million people were internally displaced whereas 400,000 refugees left Ethiopia.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] According to Human Rights Watch, more than half its mortality could be attributed to "human rights abuses causing the famine to come earlier, strike harder and extend further than would otherwise have been the case".
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] According to the United States Agency for International Development, "in the fall of 1984, the hardest hit regions were Tigray, Wollo, and Eritrea – areas with extremely limited road and transportation networks.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Moreover, these regions were the scenes of longstanding anti-government rebellions which created precarious security situations." Other areas of Ethiopia experienced famine for similar reasons, resulting in tens of thousands of additional deaths.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The famine as a whole took place a decade into the Ethiopian Civil War.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Since 1991, the favoured explanation for the famine of 1983–1985 is "war and drought".
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Throughout the feudal era, famines were common in Ethiopia, especially in the north.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Local famines were also frequent but also unrecorded.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The most infamous was the "Great Ethiopian Famine" which killed approximately one third of Ethiopia's population between 1888 and 1892.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In 1973, drought and feudal extractions caused a famine that killed 40,000 to 200,000 people in Wollo, resulting in protests in the capital of Addis Ababa, with Amhara youth decrying the seemingly ignored famine.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Despite attempts to suppress news of this famine, leaked reports contributed to the undermining of the government's legitimacy and served as a rallying point for dissidents, who complained that the wealthy classes and the Ethiopian government had ignored both the famine and the people who had died.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Then in 1974, a group of military officers known as the Derg overthrew Haile Selassie.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The Derg addressed the Wollo famine by creating the Relief and Rehabilitation Commission (RRC) to examine the causes of the famine and prevent its recurrence, and then abolishing feudal tenure in March 1975.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The RRC initially enjoyed more independence from the Derg than any other ministry, largely due to its close ties to foreign donors and the quality of some of its senior staff.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] As a result, insurgencies began to spread into the country's administrative regions.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] By late 1976 insurgencies existed in all of the country's fourteen administrative regions.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The Red Terror (1976–1978) marked the beginning of a steady deterioration in the economic state of the nation, coupled with extractive policies targeting rural areas.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The reforms of 1975 were revoked and the Agricultural Marketing Corporation (AMC) was tasked with extracting food from rural peasantry at low rates to placate the urban populations.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The very low fixed price of grain served as a disincentive to production, and some peasants had to buy grain on the open market in order to meet their AMC quota.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Citizens in Wollo, which continued to be stricken with drought, were required to provide a "famine relief tax" to the AMC until 1984.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The Derg also imposed a system of travel permits to restrict peasants from engaging in non-agricultural activities, such as petty trading and migrant labor, a major form of income supplementation.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] However, the collapse of the system of State Farms, a large employer of seasonal laborers, resulted in an estimated 500,000 farmers in northern Ethiopia losing a component of their income.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Grain wholesaling was declared illegal in much of the country, resulting in the number of grain dealers falling from between 20,000 and 30,000 to 4,942 in the decade after the revolution.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The nature of the RRC changed as the government became increasingly authoritarian.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Immediately after its creation, its experienced core of technocrats produced highly regarded analyses of Ethiopian famine and ably carried out famine relief efforts.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] However, by the 1980s, the Derg had compromised its mission.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The RRC began with the innocuous scheme of creating village workforces from the unemployed in state farms, and government agricultural schemes but, as the counter-insurgency intensified, the RRC was given responsibility for a program of forced resettlement and villagization.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] As the go-between for international aid organizations and foreign donor governments, the RRC redirected food to government militias, in particular in Eritrea and Tigray.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] It also encouraged international agencies to set up relief programs in regions with surplus grain production, which allowed the AMC to collect the excess food.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Finally, the RRC carried out a disinformation campaign during the 1980s famine, in which it portrayed the famine as being solely the result of drought and overpopulation and tried to deny the existence of the armed conflict that was occurring precisely in the famine-affected regions.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The RRC also claimed that the aid being given by it and its international agency partners were reaching all of the famine victims.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Due to organized government policies that deliberately multiplied the effects of the famine, around 1.2 million people died in Ethiopia from the famine where the majority of the death tolls were from the present day Tigray Region and Amhara Region and other parts of northern Ethiopia.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Before the 1983–1985 famine, two decades of wars of national liberation and other anti-government conflict had raged throughout northern Ethiopia and present-day Eritrea.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The most prominent feature of the fighting was the use of indiscriminate violence against civilians by the Ethiopian Army and Air Force.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Excluding those killed by famine and resettlement, more than 150,000 people were killed.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The economy of Ethiopia is based on agriculture: almost half of GDP, 60% of exports, and 80% of total employment come from agriculture.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Four Ethiopian provinces — Gojjam, Hararghe, Tigray and Wollo — all received record low rainfalls in the mid-1980s.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In the south, a separate and simultaneous cause was the government's response to Oromo Liberation Front (OLF) insurgency.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In 1984, Mengistu Haile Mariam announced that 46% of the Ethiopian Gross National Product would be allocated to military spending, creating the largest standing army in sub-Saharan Africa; the allocation for health in the government budget fell from 6% in 1973–1974 to 3% by 1990–1991.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Although a UN estimate of one million deaths is often quoted for the 1983–1985 famine, this figure has been challenged by famine scholar Alex de Waal.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In a major study, de Waal criticized the United Nations for being "remarkably cavalier" about the numbers of people who died, with the UN's one-million figure having "absolutely no scientific basis whatsoever," a fact which represents "a trivialization and dehumanization of human misery".
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] De Waal estimates that 400,000 to 500,000 died in the famine.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Nevertheless, the magnitude of the disaster has been well documented: in addition to hundreds of thousands of deaths, millions were made destitute.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Media activity in the West, along with the size of the crisis, led to the "Do They Know It's Christmas?" charity single and the July 1985 concert Live Aid, which elevated the international profile of the famine and helped secure international aid.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In the early to mid-1980s there were famines in two distinct regions of the country, resulting in several studies of one famine that try to extrapolate to the other or less cautious writers referring to a single widespread famine.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The famine in the southeast of the country was brought about by the Derg's counterinsurgency efforts against the OLF.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] However, most media referring to "the Ethiopian famine" of the 1980s refers to the severe famine in 1983–85 centered on Tigray and northern Wollo, which further affected Eritrea, Begemder and northern Shewa.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Living standards had been declining in these government-held regions since 1977, a "direct consequence" of the Derg's agricultural policies.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] A further major contributing factor to the famine were the Ethiopian government's enforced resettlement programs, utilized as part of its counter-insurgency campaign.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Despite RRC claims to have predicted the famine, there was little data as late as early 1984 indicating an unusually severe food shortage.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Following two major droughts in the late 1970s, 1980 and 1981 were rated by the RRC as "normal" and "above normal".
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The 1982 harvest was the largest ever, with the exception of central and eastern Tigray.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] RRC estimates for people "at-risk" of famine rose to 3.9 million in 1983 from 2.8 million in 1982, which was less than the 1981 estimate of 4.5 million.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In February and March 1983, the first signs of famine were recognized as poverty-stricken farmers began to appear at feeding centers, prompting international aid agencies to appeal for aid and the RRC to revise its famine assessment.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The harvest after the main (*meher*) harvest in 1983 was the third largest on record, with the only serious shortfall again being recorded in Tigray.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In response, grain prices in the two northern regions of Begemder and Gojjam fell.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The RRC claimed in May 1984 that the failure of the short rains (*belg*) constituted a catastrophic drought while neglecting to state that the *belg* crops form a fourth of crop yields where the *belg* falls, but none at all in the majority of Tigray.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] A quantitative measure of the famine are grain prices, which show high prices in eastern and central Tigray, spreading outward after the 1984 crop failure.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] A major drain on Ethiopia's economy was the ongoing civil war, which pitched rebel movements against the Soviet and Cuban-backed Derg government.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] This crippled the country's economy further and contributed to the government's lack of ability to handle the crisis to come.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] By mid-1984, it was evident that another drought and resulting famine of major proportions had begun to affect large parts of northern Ethiopia.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Just as evident was the government's inability to provide relief.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The almost total failure of crops in the north was compounded by fighting in and around Eritrea, which hindered the passage of relief supplies.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Although international relief organizations made a major effort to provide food to the affected areas, the persistence of drought and poor security conditions in the north resulted in continuing need as well as hazards for famine relief workers.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In late 1985, another year of drought was forecast, and by early 1986 the famine had spread to parts of the southern highlands, with an estimated 5.8 million people dependent on relief food.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In 1986, locust plagues exacerbated the problem.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Despite the fact that the government had access to only a minority of the famine-stricken population in the north, the great majority of the relief was channeled through the government side, prolonging the war.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The Ethiopian government's unwillingness to deal with the famine provoked universal condemnation by the international community.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Even many supporters of the Ethiopian regime opposed its policy of withholding food shipments to rebel areas.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The combined effects of famine and internal war had by then put the nation's economy into a state of decline.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The primary government response to the drought and famine was the decision to uproot large numbers of peasants who lived in the affected areas in the north and to resettle them in the west and southern part of the country.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In 1985 and 1986, about 600,000 people were moved, many forcibly, from their home villages and farms by the military and transported to various regions in the south.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Many peasants fled rather than allow themselves to be resettled; many of those who were resettled sought later to return to their native regions.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Several human rights organizations claimed that tens of thousands of peasants died as a result of forced resettlement.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] According to Human Rights Watch, at least 50,000 people died.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Another government plan involved villagization, which was a response not only to the famine but also to the poor security situation.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Beginning in 1985, peasants were forced to move their homesteads into planned villages, which were clustered around water, schools, medical services, and utility supply points to facilitate the distribution of those services.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Many peasants fled rather than acquiesce in relocation, which in general proved highly unpopular.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Additionally, the government in most cases failed to provide the promised services.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Far from benefiting agricultural productivity, the program caused a decline in food production.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Although temporarily suspended in 1986, villagization was subsequently resumed.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Close to 8 million people became famine victims during the drought of 1984, and over 1 million died.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In the same year (23 October), a BBC news crew was the first to document the famine, with Michael Buerk describing "a biblical famine in the 20th century" and "the closest thing to hell on Earth".
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The report shocked Britain, motivating its citizens to inundate relief agencies, such as Save the Children, with donations, and also to bring the world's attention to the crisis in Ethiopia.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In November 1984, the British Royal Air Force carried out the first airdrops from C-130 Hercules delivering food to the starving people.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Other countries including Sweden, East and West Germany, Poland, Canada, United States, the Soviet Union and Yugoslavia were also involved in the international response.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Buerk's news piece on the BBC was seen by Irish singer Bob Geldof, who quickly organised the charity supergroup Band Aid, primarily made up of the biggest British and Irish artists of the era.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Their single, "Do They Know It's Christmas?", was released on 3 December 1984 and became Britain's best-selling single within a few weeks, eventually selling 3.69 million copies domestically.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] It raised £8 million for famine relief within twelve months of its release.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Other charity singles soon followed; released in March 1985, "We Are the World" by USA for Africa was the most successful of these, selling 20 million copies worldwide.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Live Aid, a 1985 fund-raising effort headed by Geldof, induced millions of people in the West to donate money and to urge their governments to participate in the relief effort in Ethiopia.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Some of the proceeds also went to the famine hit areas of Eritrea.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In France, supergroup Chanteurs sans frontières released "SOS Éthiopie", which sold 1 million copies and raised 10 million francs (about 1.2 million dollars).
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In Canada, supergroup Northern Lights, consisting of Bryan Adams, The Guess Who, Rush, Anne Murray, John Candy, Neil Young, and among others sang "Tears Are Not Enough", which was produced by David Foster.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] In Yugoslavia, supergroup YU Rock Misija recorded the charity single "Za milion godina" and organized a corresponding charity concert, raising a total of US$426,000.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Other charity initiatives raised money for Ethiopia.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] On 27 January 1985, members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints participated in a special fast, where members went without food for two meals and donated the money they would have used to buy food.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The fast raised $6 million for the famine victims in Ethiopia.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The manner in which international aid was routed through the RRC gave rise to criticism that forever changed the way in which governments and NGOs respond to international emergencies taking place within conflict situations.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] International aid supplied to the government and to relief agencies working alongside the government became part of the counter-insurgency strategy of the government.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] It, therefore, met a real and immediate need but also prolonged the life of Mengistu's government.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The response to the emergency raised disturbing questions about the relationship between humanitarian agencies and host governments.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] However, according to Peter Gill, in his 2010 book *Foreigners and Famine: Ethiopia Since Live Aid*, 7.9 million people faced starvation in 1984, resulting in over 600,000 deaths; while in 2003 13.2 million "faced the prospect of a famine and only 300 died".
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] On 3 March 2010, Martin Plaut of the BBC published evidence that millions of dollars' worth of aid to the Ethiopian famine were spent in buying weapons by the Tigrayan People's Liberation Front, a communist group trying to overthrow the Ethiopian communist government at the time.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Rebel soldiers said they posed as merchants as "a trick for the NGOs".
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The report also cited a CIA document saying aid was "almost certainly being diverted for military purposes".
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] One rebel leader estimated $95 million (£63 million).
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Plaut also said that other NGOs were under the influence or control of the Derg military junta.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Some journalists suggested that the Derg was able to use Live Aid and Oxfam money to fund its enforced resettlement and villagization programs, under which at least 3 million people are said to have been displaced and between 50,000 and 100,000 killed.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] The United States Agency for International Development which provided foreign assistance during the famine, estimated that "more than 300,000" died.
[src:bbc-news/1983-1985-famine-in-ethiopia] Other insider estimates put the total death toll in Ethiopia at "1.2 million dead, 400,000 refugees outside the country, 2.5 million people internally displaced, and almost 200,000 orphans".
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The **1996 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the XXVI Olympiad**, also known as **Atlanta 1996** and commonly referred to as the **Centennial Olympic Games**) were an international multi-sport event held from July 19 to August 4, 1996, in Atlanta, Georgia, United States.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] These were the fourth Summer Olympics to be hosted by the United States, making it the first country to have three different cities host the Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] It also marked the 100th anniversary of the 1896 Summer Olympics in Athens, the inaugural edition of the modern Olympic Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] These were also the first Summer Olympics to be held in a different year than the Winter Olympics since the Winter Olympics commenced in 1924, as part of a new IOC practice implemented in 1994 to hold the Summer and Winter Games in alternating, even-numbered years.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The 1996 Games were the first of the two consecutive Summer Olympics to be held in a predominantly English-speaking country, preceding the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] These were also the last Summer Olympics to be held in North America until 2028, when Los Angeles will host the games for the third time.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] A total of 24 countries made their Summer Olympic debuts in Atlanta, including 11 former Soviet republics participating for the first time as independent nations.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] With a total of 101 medals, the United States topped both the gold and overall medal count for the first time since 1984 (and for the first time since 1968 in a non-boycotted Summer Olympics), also winning the most gold (44) and silver (32) medals out of all the participating nations.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The Games were marred by violence on July 27, 1996, when a pipe bomb was detonated at Centennial Olympic Park (which had been built to serve as a public focal point for the festivities), killing two and injuring 111.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Years later, Eric Rudolph confessed to the bombing and a series of related terrorist attacks, and was sentenced to life in prison.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Nonetheless, the 1996 Olympics turned a profit, helped by record revenue from sponsorship deals and broadcast rights, and a reliance on private funding, among other factors.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] There were 8.3 million tickets sold for events at this Olympics, a record broken only in 2024.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] There was some criticism of the perceived over-commercialization of the Games, with other issues raised by European officials, such as the availability of food and transport.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Atlanta was selected on September 18, 1990, in Tokyo, Japan, over Athens, Belgrade, Manchester, Melbourne, and Toronto at the 96th IOC Session.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The city entered the competition as a dark horse, being up against stiff competition.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The US media also criticized Atlanta as a second-tier city and complained of Georgia's Confederate history.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] However, the IOC Evaluation Commission ranked Atlanta's infrastructure and facilities the highest, while IOC members said that it could guarantee large television revenues similar to the success of the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, the most recent Olympics in the United States.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Additionally, former US ambassador to the UN and Atlanta mayor Andrew Young touted Atlanta's civil rights history and reputation for racial harmony.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Young also wanted to showcase a reformed American South.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The strong economy of Atlanta and improved race relations in the South helped to impress the IOC officials.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Coca-Cola, a long-standing partner of the Olympics, was also a strong advocate to bring the Games to its hometown.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games (ACOG) also proposed a substantial revenue-sharing with the IOC, USOC, and other NOCs.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] This would be Toronto's fourth failed attempt since 1960 (tried in 1960, 1964, and 1976, but was defeated by Rome, Tokyo and Montreal).
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Greece, the home of the ancient and first modern Olympics, was considered by many observers the "natural choice" for the Centennial Games, due to its "divine right" in history.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Athens bid chairman Spyros Metaxas gave repeated warnings to the IOC and demanded to give them the games to mark the centennial, saying "You don't hold a 100th birthday in someone else's home.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] However, the Athens bid was described as "arrogant and poorly prepared," being regarded as "not being up to the task of coping with the modern and risk-prone extravaganza" of the current Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The total cost of the 1996 Summer Olympics was estimated to be around US$1.7 billion.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] In total, the Games turned a profit of $19 million.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The cost for Atlanta 1996 compares with costs of $4.6 billion for Rio 2016, $40–44 billion for Beijing 2008, and $51 billion for Sochi 2014 Winter Olympics (the most expensive Olympic Games without differentiating between summer and winter in history).
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The average cost for the Summer Games since 1960 is $5.2 billion.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Using the 1984 Summer Olympics financing model, this edition was organized 100% privately without any cent of public money.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Beijing 2008 and Sochi 2014 were financed entirely by the governments of their respective countries.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] ACOG budgeted $32.7 million for Atlanta Police Department and Georgia Department of Public Safety services during the games. $70 million in funding came from the U.S. federal government for additional services, including 500 additional federal agents.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Transportation relied heavily on an expanded MARTA rail and 3,000 additional buses borrowed from nationwide transit agencies.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Ticketed events came with free public transportation.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Shuttles were provided for VIPs, athletes and olympic officials.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] These shuttles connected remote Park 'N Ride lots, central terminals, and specific competition venues.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The city implemented new High-Occupancy Vehicle lanes on I-75 and I-85 highways and coordinated traffic from a centralized Traffic Management Center to handle the daily crowds that often exceeded 500,000 people.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The games were challenged by driver shortages, route navigation errors, and logistical delays.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Events of the 1996 Games were held in a completely decentralized way using mostly existing facilities that were not built for the Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Most of the events were held in the so-called Olympic Ring, a 3 mi (4.8 km) circle from the center of Atlanta.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Others were held at Stone Mountain, about 20 miles (32 km) outside of the city.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] In many cases, it was decided to remove events from the Atlanta Metropolitan Region to save money, while in others the calendar was a difficulty, as was the case with association football (soccer) which ended up having its host cities spread across the Southeastern United States region.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] During early planning stages in 1992, Payne and the ACOG wanted a golf event to be held at Augusta National Golf Club.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Initially, Augusta agreed, but protests from civil rights leaders and politicians against the club's strict admission policies led to the collapse of the idea.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The Olympic Arts Festival offered 200 ticketed events, including more than 20 exhibitions in local institutions, museums, and gallery spaces.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] More than 3,000 artists participated during the two weeks of the Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] There were numerous free events including a daily series of music at Centennial Olympic Park, called "Southern Crossroads".
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] In 1994, African-American artist Kevin Cole was commissioned to create the Coca-Cola Centennial Olympic Wall, and the 15-story mural took two years to complete.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The Olympiad's official theme, "Summon the Heroes", was written by John Williams, making it the third Olympiad at that point for which he had composed (official composer in 1984, NBC's coverage composer in 1988).
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The opening ceremony featured Céline Dion singing "The Power of the Dream", the theme song of the 1996 Olympics.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The closing ceremony featured Gloria Estefan singing "Reach", the official theme song of the 1996 Olympics.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The torch relay was run from April 27 to July 19, leading up to the Games in Atlanta.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The route covered 26,875 kilometers (16,699 mi) across the United States.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The relay involved over 12,000 torchbearers, including Muhammad Ali, who was chosen to ignite the flame at the opening ceremony.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] 8.32 million tickets were sold, a record recently broken by Paris 2024.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Ticket sales brought in $420 million for the ACOG, 1/4 of its operating budget.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The "Look of the Games" design for Atlanta 1996 was named "Quilt of Leaves".
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The graphic identity featured a quilting leaf pattern.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Representing a city coming together—with laurel leaves.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The "Quilt of Leaves" theme appeared across official venues, signage, tickets, credentials, and even physically minted into the back of the Atlanta 1996 Olympic Medals.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The logo was designed by Landor Associates, it featured the Olympic flame and stars in five vibrant colors above the number 100.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The base resembled a classical Greek column to celebrate the centennial of the modern Olympic Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The main backdrop color was: *Georgia forest green*.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] It represented green laurels branches worn by winners in ancient Greece as well as Atlanta being nicknamed "city of trees".
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The colors palette featured *khaki gold*, *tomato orange*, *magenta*, *blue* and *purple*.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Atlanta's Olympic slogan "Come Celebrate Our Dream" was written by Jack Arogeti, a managing director at McCann-Erickson in Atlanta at the time.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The slogan was selected from more than 5,000 submitted by the public to the Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Izzy was an abstract, amorphous tech-generated blue fantasy figure character wearing white gloves and red shoes.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] In contrast to the standing tradition of mascots of national or regional significance to the city hosting.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Created by John Ryan, an Atlanta animator from the DESIGNefx firm.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] A video game featuring the Games' mascot, *Izzy's Quest for the Olympic Rings*, was also released.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The 1996 Summer Olympics relied heavily on commercial sponsorship, 111 total domestic corporate partners.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Company was the exclusive provider of soft drinks at Olympics venues, and built an attraction known as Coca-Cola Olympic City for the Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] As part of a sponsorship agreement with Columbia TriStar Television, the syndicated game shows *Jeopardy!* and *Wheel of Fortune* both produced episodes with Olympics tie-ins (including branded memorabilia and contests) for broadcast between April and July 1996.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] These included a *Jeopardy!* international tournament, and three weeks of *Wheel of Fortune* episodes filmed on-location at Atlanta's Fox Theatre.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The Atlanta organizing committee threatened legal actions against advertisers whose marketing implied an official association with the Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Several non-sponsors set up marketing activities in areas near venues, such as Samsung (competing with Motorola), which ambushed the Games with its "96 Expo".
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The city of Atlanta had also licensed street vendors to sell products from competitors to Olympic sponsors.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Nike also opened a pop-up store known as the Nike Center near the Athletes' Village, which distributed Nike-branded flags to visitors (presumably to be used at events).
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] IOC marketing director Michael Payne expressed concern for the campaign, believing that athletes could perceive them as being an insult to their accomplishments.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Payne and the United States Olympic Committee's marketing director, John Krimsky, met with Howard Slusher, a subordinate of Nike co-founder Phil Knight.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Faced with these threats, Nike agreed to retract most of its negative advertising and public relations stunts.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] A total of 197 nations, all of the then-existing and recognized National Olympic Committees, were represented at the 1996 Games, and the combined total of athletes was about 10,318.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Twenty-four countries made their Olympic debut this year, including eleven of the ex-Soviet countries that competed as part of the Unified Team in 1992.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Russia participated in the Summer Olympics separately from the other countries of the former Soviet Union for the first time since 1912 (when it was the Russian Empire).
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Russia had been a member of the Unified Team at the 1992 Summer Olympics together with 11 post-Soviet states.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia competed as *Yugoslavia*.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] After missing the 1992 Summer Games Afghanistan and Cambodia returned to send delegations to Atlanta.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The 14 countries making their Olympic debut were: Azerbaijan, Burundi, Cape Verde, Comoros, Dominica, Guinea-Bissau, Macedonia, Nauru, Palestinian Authority, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Saint Lucia, São Tomé and Príncipe, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The ten countries making their Summer Olympic debut (after competing at the 1994 Winter Olympics in Lillehammer) were: Armenia, Belarus, Czech Republic, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Slovakia, Ukraine and Uzbekistan.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The Czech Republic and Slovakia attended the games as independent nations for the first time since the breakup of Czechoslovakia, while the rest of the nations that made their Summer Olympic debut were formerly part of the Soviet Union.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] 10,339 athletes from 197 NOCs participated in the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The ceremony began with a 60-second countdown, which included footage from all of the previous Olympic Games at twenty-two seconds.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] There was then a flashback to the closing ceremony of the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona, showing the then president of the IOC, Juan Antonio Samaranch, inviting the athletes to compete in Atlanta in 1996.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Then, spirits ascended in the northwest corner of the stadium, each representing one of the colors in the Olympic rings.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The spirits called the tribes of the world which, after mixed percussion, formed the Olympic rings while the youth of Atlanta formed the number 100.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Famed film score composer John Williams wrote the official overture for the 1996 Olympics, called "Summon the Heroes"; this was his second overture for Olympic games, the first being "Olympic Fanfare and Theme" written for the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Céline Dion performed David Foster's official 1996 Olympics song "The Power of the Dream", accompanied by Foster on the piano, the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra and the Centennial Choir (comprising Morehouse College Glee Club, Spelman College Glee Club and the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra Chorus).
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Gladys Knight sang Georgia's official state song, "Georgia on My Mind".
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] There was another showcase entitled "Summertime" which focused on Atlanta and the Old South, emphasizing its beauty, spirit, music, history, culture, and rebirth after the American Civil War.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The ceremony also featured a memorable dance tribute to the athletes and to the goddesses of victory of the ancient Greek Olympics, using silhouette imagery.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The accompanying music, "The Tradition of the Games", was composed by Basil Poledouris.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Muhammad Ali lit the Olympic cauldron and later received a replacement gold medal for his boxing victory in the 1960 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] For the torch ceremony, more than 10,000 Olympic torches were manufactured by the American Meter Company, electroplated by Klein Plating Works, and polished by Erie Plating Company.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Each torch weighed about 3.5 pounds (1.6 kg) and was made primarily of aluminum, with a Georgia pecan wood handle and gold ornamentation.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The city of Savannah, Georgia, host of the yachting events, also held their own opening ceremony on the first day of their competitions.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The event was headlined by a performance by country musician Trisha Yearwood.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The 1996 Summer Olympic program featured 271 events in 26 sports.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Softball, beach volleyball and mountain biking debuted on the Olympic program, together with women's football, lightweight events in rowing, Women's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay in swimming, the Women's épée in fencing and the group all-around event in rhythmic gymnastics.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1996 Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Domestic network NBC bought the broadcasting rights for US$456 million.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The European Broadcasting Union paid US$240 million.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The 1996 Olympics were marred by the Centennial Olympic Park bombing, which occurred on July 27.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Security guard Richard Jewell discovered the pipe bomb and immediately notified law enforcement, helping to evacuate as many people as possible from the area before it exploded.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Although Jewell's quick actions are credited for saving many lives, the bombing killed spectator Alice Hawthorne, wounded 111 others, and caused the death of Melih Uzunyol by a heart attack.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Jewell was later considered a suspect in the bombing but was never charged, and he was cleared in October 1996.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Fugitive Eric Rudolph was arrested in May 2003 and charged with the Olympic Park bombing as well as the bombings of two abortion clinics and a gay nightclub.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Preparations for the Olympics lasted more than seven years and had an economic impact of at least US$5.14 billion.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Over two million visitors came to Atlanta, and approximately 3.5 billion people around the world watched at least some of the events on television.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Although marred by the tragedy of the Centennial Olympic Park bombing, the Games were a financial success, due in part to TV rights contracts and sponsorships at record levels.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Atlanta also set a new record for the most tickets sold at a single Games (8.3 million), and held it until 2024.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Beyond international recognition, the Games resulted in many modern infrastructure improvements.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The mid-rise dormitories built for the Olympic Village, which became the first residential housing for Georgia State University (Georgia State Village), are now used by the Georgia Institute of Technology (North Avenue Apartments).
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] As designed, the Centennial Olympic Stadium was converted into Turner Field after the Paralympics, which became the home of the Atlanta Braves Major League Baseball team from 1997 to 2016.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The Braves' former home, Atlanta–Fulton County Stadium, was demolished in 1997 and the site became a parking lot for Turner Field; the Omni Coliseum was demolished the same year to make way for State Farm Arena.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The city's permanent memorial to the 1996 Olympics is Centennial Olympic Park, which was built as a focal point for the Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The park initiated a revitalization of the surrounding area and now serves as the hub for Atlanta's tourism district.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] In November 2016, a commemorative plaque was unveiled for Centennial Olympic Park to honor the 20th anniversary of the Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Following the Braves' departure from Turner Field to Truist Park in 2017, Georgia State University acquired the former Olympic Stadium and surrounding parking lots.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] It reconfigured the stadium for a second time into Center Parc Stadium for its college football team.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The 1996 Olympic cauldron was originally built and placed at the intersection of Fulton Street and Capitol Avenue, near the Centennial Olympic Stadium.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] After the Paralympics, in order to make room for the stadium conversion, the Olympic cauldron was moved (except its ramp, which was demolished) to the intersection of Capitol Avenue and Fulton Street in 1997, where it has stayed since.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Since Georgia State University's acquisition of the former Olympic Stadium and surrounding lots, there has been proposals and growing calls to move the Olympic cauldron to Centennial Olympic Park.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The Olympic cauldron was re-lit in February 2020 for the 2020 U.S.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The 1996 Olympics are the most recent edition of the Summer Olympics to be held in the United States.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Los Angeles will host the 2028 Summer Olympics, 32 years after the Games were held in Atlanta.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] In 1997, Athens was awarded the 2004 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Along with addressing the shortcomings of its 1996 bid, it was lauded for its efforts to promote the traditional values of the Olympic Games, which some IOC observers felt had been lost due to the over-commercialization of the 1996 Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] However, the 2004 Games heavily relied on public funding and eventually failed to make a profit, which some have claimed contributed to the financial crisis in Greece.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The financial struggles faced by many later Games, such as the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin and the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, have caused some to offer more positive reappraisals of the management of the 1996 Summer Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] Former JPMorgan Chase president (and torchbearer) Kabir Sehgal noted that in contrast to many later Olympics, those of 1996 were financially viable, had a positive economic impact on the city, and most of the facilities constructed continued to be used after the Games.
[src:bbc-news/1996-olympic-games] The 2028 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles will rely almost entirely on private funding, with the city of Los Angeles and state of California each intending to provide up to $250 million in funding in the event of shortfalls, and the U.S. federal government providing funding solely for security.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday, 1 May 1997.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The governing Conservative Party led by Prime Minister John Major was defeated in a landslide by the opposition Labour Party led by Tony Blair, which achieved a 177-seat majority and a total of 418 seats.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This was the first victory for the Labour party in a general election in nearly 23 years, its previous one registering a majority of 3 seats in October 1974 under the leadership of Harold Wilson.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] It was also Labour's first comprehensive victory over the Conservatives since the 1966 election, which had produced a 98-seat majority.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This election also marked Labour's highest vote share since the 1970 election and its second highest total number of votes in history (the largest being the 1951 election).
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] On the other hand, it was an ignominious end to the 18-year government of the Conservatives, the longest continuous period of government of any party in modern British history.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This election marked the third-largest defeat ever suffered by the Conservatives (the largest being the 2024 election) with the party left with just 165 seats—it was left devoid of any MPs outside England, with only 17 MPs north of the Midlands, and with less than 20% of MPs in London.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Additionally, the party also registered its lowest share of the vote since 1832 as well as its lowest vote in absolute terms since 1929.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This would be the last election until 2024 that the Conservatives decreased their share of the vote.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The final result of the election on 2 May 1997 revealed that Labour had won a landslide majority, making a net gain of 146 seats and winning 43.2% of the vote.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] 150 Members of Parliament, including 133 Conservatives, lost their seats.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives, meanwhile, suffered defeat with a net loss of 178 seats, winning 30.7% of the vote.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats led by Paddy Ashdown made a net gain of 28 seats, winning 16.8% of the vote.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour's victory, the largest achieved in its history and by any political party in British politics since the Second World War, brought about the party's first of three consecutive terms in power (lasting a total of 13 years), with Blair as the newly appointed prime minister.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats' success in the election, in part due to anti-Conservative tactical voting, strengthened both Ashdown's leadership and the party's position as a strong third party, having won the highest number of seats by any third party since 1929.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The election of 120 women, including 101 to the Labour benches, came to be seen as a watershed moment in female political representation in the UK.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The British economy had been in recession at the time of the 1992 general election, which the governing Conservative Party led by John Major had won.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The recession ended within a year, but later events such as Black Wednesday severely tarnished the Conservative government's reputation for economic management.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Meanwhile, the opposition Labour Party elected John Smith as its leader in 1992 to succeed Neil Kinnock; however, Smith's death from a heart attack in 1994 led to a leadership election which was won by Shadow Home Secretary Tony Blair.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Blair sought to bring the party closer to the political centre of the era, including rebranding the party as "New Labour".
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] He convinced the party's members and affiliated trades unions to support the removal of Clause IV from its constitution, which had committed it to the mass nationalisation of industry, and the party also reversed its policy on unilateral nuclear disarmament.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The events of Black Wednesday also meant Labour—and shadow chancellor Gordon Brown—were perceived as offering more competent economic management than the Conservatives.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Disputes within the Conservative government over European Union issues, and a variety of "sleaze" allegations, severely affected the government's popularity.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite the economic recovery and fall in unemployment in the four years leading up to the election, the rise in Conservative support was only marginal, with all of the major opinion polls showing Labour in a comfortable lead from late 1992 onwards.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the 1992 general election, the Conservatives remained in government with 336 of the 651 House of Commons seats, but through a series of defections and by-election defeats the government gradually lost its absolute majority.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] By 1997, the Conservatives held only 324 seats and had not won a by-election since Richmond in 1989.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The previous Parliament first sat on 27 April 1992.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Parliament Act 1911 required at the time for each Parliament to be dissolved on the fifth anniversary of its first sitting; therefore, the latest date the dissolution and the summoning of the next parliament could have been held on was 27 April 1997.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The 1985 amendment of the Representation of the People Act 1983 required that the election must take place on the eleventh working day after the deadline for nomination papers, which in turn must be no more than six working days after the next parliament was summoned.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Therefore, the latest date the election could have been held on was 22 May 1997 (which happened to be a Thursday).
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] British elections (and referendums) have been held on Thursdays by convention since the 1930s, but can be held on other working days.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Major called the election on Monday 17 March 1997, ensuring the formal campaign would be unusually long, at six weeks (Parliament was dissolved on 8 April).
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was scheduled for 1 May, to coincide with the local elections on the same day.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This set a precedent, as the three subsequent general elections were also held alongside the May local elections.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives argued that a long campaign would expose Labour and allow the Conservative message to be heard.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] However, Major was accused of arranging an early dissolution to protect Neil Hamilton from a pending parliamentary report into his conduct: a report that Major had earlier guaranteed would be published before the election.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] In March 1997, soon after the election was called, Asda introduced a range of election-themed beers, these being "Major's Mild", "Tony's Tipple" and "Ashdown's Ale".
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The political backdrop of campaigning focused on public opinion towards a change in government.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Opinion polls during campaigning showed strong support for Labour due to Blair's personal popularity, and Blair won a personal public endorsement from *The Sun* newspaper two months before the vote.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Major hoped that a long campaign would expose Labour's "hollowness" and the Conservative campaign emphasised stability, as did its manifesto title 'You can only be sure with the Conservatives'.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] However, the campaign was beset by deep-set problems, such as the rise of James Goldsmith's Referendum Party which advocated a referendum on continued membership of the European Union.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The party threatened to take away many right-leaning voters from the Conservatives.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Furthermore, about 200 candidates broke with official Conservative policy to oppose British membership of the single European currency.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Major fought back, saying: "Whether you agree with me or disagree with me; like me or loathe me, don't bind my hands when I am negotiating on behalf of the British nation." The moment is remembered as one of the defining, and most surreal, moments of the election.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Meanwhile, there was also division amongst the Conservative cabinet, with Chancellor Kenneth Clarke describing the views of Home Secretary Michael Howard on Europe as "paranoid and xenophobic nonsense".
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The New Labour, New Danger poster, which depicted Tony Blair with demon eyes, was an example of the latter strategy.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Major veered between the two approaches, which left Conservative Central Office staff frustrated.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] As Andrew Cooper explained: "We repeatedly tried and failed to get him to understand that you couldn't say that they were dangerous and copying you at the same time." In any case, the campaign failed to gain much traction, and the Conservatives went down to a landslide defeat at the polls.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour ran a slick campaign that emphasised the splits within the Conservative government and argued that the country needed a more centrist administration.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] It thus successfully picked up dissatisfied Conservative voters, particularly moderate and suburban ones.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Tony Blair, who was personally highly popular, was very much the centrepiece of the campaign and proved a highly effective campaigner.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour campaign was reminiscent of those of Bill Clinton for the US presidency in 1992 and 1996, focusing on centrist themes as well as adopting policies more commonly associated with the right, such as cracking down on crime and fiscal responsibility.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The influence of political "spin" came into great effect for Labour at this point, as media centric figures such as Alastair Campbell and Peter Mandelson provided a clear cut campaign, and establishing a relatively new political brand New Labour with enviable success.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] In this election Labour adopted the theme Things Can Only Get Better in their campaign and advertising.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Lib Dems promised to increase education funding paid for by a 1p increase in income tax.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was fought under new boundaries, with a net increase of eight seats compared to the 1992 election (651 to 659).
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Changes listed here are from the notional 1992 result, had it been fought on the boundaries established in 1997.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] These notional results were calculated by Colin Rallings and Michael Thrasher and were used by all media organisations at the time.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour won a landslide victory with its largest parliamentary majority (177) to date.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] On the BBC's election night programme Professor Anthony King described the result of the exit poll, which accurately predicted a Labour landslide, as being akin to "an asteroid hitting the planet and destroying practically all life on Earth".
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] After years of trying, Labour had convinced the electorate that they would usher in a new age of prosperity—their policies, organisation and tone of optimism slotting perfectly into place.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour's victory was largely credited to the charisma of Tony Blair, as well as a Labour public relations machine managed by Alastair Campbell and Peter Mandelson.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Between the 1992 election and the 1997 election there had also been major steps to "modernise" the party, including scrapping Clause IV that had committed the party to extending public ownership of industry.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour had suddenly seized the middle ground of the political spectrum, attracting voters much further to the right than their traditional working class or left wing support.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was a crushing defeat for the Conservatives, with the party having its lowest percentage share of the popular vote since 1832 under the Duke of Wellington's leadership, being wiped out in Scotland and Wales.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] A number of prominent Conservative MPs lost their seats in the election, including Michael Portillo, Malcolm Rifkind, Edwina Currie, David Mellor, Neil Hamilton and Norman Lamont.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Such was the extent of Conservative losses at the election that Cecil Parkinson, speaking on the BBC's election night programme, joked upon the Conservatives winning their second seat that he was pleased that the subsequent election for the leadership would be contested.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats stood on a more left-wing manifesto than Labour, and more than doubled their number of seats thanks to the use of tactical voting against the Conservatives.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Although their share of the vote fell slightly, their total of 46 MPs was the highest for any UK Liberal party since David Lloyd George led the party to 59 seats in 1929.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Referendum Party, which sought a referendum on the United Kingdom's relationship with the European Union, came fourth in terms of votes with 800,000 votes and won no seats in parliament.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The six parties with the next highest votes stood only in either Scotland, Northern Ireland or Wales; in order, they were the Scottish National Party, the Ulster Unionist Party, the Social Democratic and Labour Party, Plaid Cymru, Sinn Féin, and the Democratic Unionist Party.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The result declared for the constituency of Winchester showed a margin of victory of just two votes for the Liberal Democrats.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This election saw a doubling of the number of women in parliament, from 60 elected in 1992 to 120 elected in 1997.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] 101 of them (controversially described as Blair Babes) were on the Labour benches, a number driven by the Labour Party's 1993 policy (ruled illegally discriminatory in 1996) of all-women shortlists.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This election has therefore been widely seen as a watershed moment for representation of women in the UK.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This election marked the start of Labour government for the next 13 years, lasting until the formation of the Conservative-Liberal Democrat coalition in 2010.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] All parties with more than 500 votes shown.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] and "Labour Time for Change" candidates; Conservative total includes candidates in Northern Ireland (excluded in some lists) and "Loyal Conservative" candidate.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Popular Unionist MP elected in 1992 died in 1995, and the party folded shortly afterwards.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] There was no incumbent Speaker in the 1992 election.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The poor results for the Conservative Party led to infighting, with the One Nation group, Tory Reform Group, and right-wing Maastricht Rebels blaming each other for the defeat.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Party chairman Brian Mawhinney said on the night of the election that defeat was due to disillusionment with 18 years of Conservative rule.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] John Major resigned as party leader, saying "When the curtain falls, it is time to get off the stage".
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Throughout this period, their representation in the Commons remained consistently below 200 MPs.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Meanwhile, Paddy Ashdown's continued leadership of the Liberal Democrats was assured, and they were felt to be in a position to build positively as a strong third party into the new millennium, culminating in their sharing power in the 2010 coalition with the Conservatives.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] With the huge rise in internet use since the previous general election, BBC News created a special website – BBC Politics 97 – covering the election.
[src:bbc-news/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This site was an experiment for the efficiency of an online news service which was due for launch later in the year.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The **2003 invasion of Iraq** was the first stage of the Iraq War.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion began on 20 March 2003 and lasted just over one month, including 26 days of major combat operations.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion was conducted by a United States-led coalition of mainly American, British, Australian, and Polish troops.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush and UK prime minister Tony Blair, the coalition aimed to disarm Iraq of weapons of mass destruction (WMDs)—nuclear, chemical, and biological weapons—and "free the Iraqi people" by deposing president Saddam Hussein, in turn ending his "support for terrorism".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Before the invasion, United Nations (UN) inspectors in Iraq had found no evidence of Iraqi WMDs; U.S. and British officials claimed they were still hidden, and posed an immediate threat to world peace.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion was strongly opposed by some long-standing U.S. allies, including Canada, France, Germany, and New Zealand.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 2004, UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan called the invasion illegal under international law, as a breach of the UN Charter.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 15 February 2003, there were worldwide protests against the anticipated invasion of Iraq, including a rally of three million people in Rome which was the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion began with an airstrike on the Presidential Palace in Baghdad on 20 March 2003.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The following day, coalition forces launched an incursion into Basra Governorate from their massing point close to the Iraqi–Kuwaiti border.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] While special forces launched an amphibious assault from the Persian Gulf to secure Basra and the surrounding petroleum fields, the main invasion army occupied southern Iraq, engaging in the Battle of Nasiriyah on 23 March.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Massive air strikes across the country and against Iraqi command and control threw the defending army into chaos and prevented an effective resistance.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 26 March, the 173rd Airborne Brigade was airdropped near the northern city of Kirkuk, where they joined forces with Kurdish rebels and fought several actions against the Iraqi Army, to secure the northern part of the country.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The main body of coalition forces continued their drive into the heart of Iraq and were met with little resistance.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Most of the Iraqi military was quickly defeated.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 9 April 2003, 22 days after the first day of the invasion, the capital city of Baghdad was captured by coalition forces after the six-day-long Battle of Baghdad.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Other operations included the capture and occupation of Kirkuk on 10 April and the attack on and capture of Tikrit on 15 April.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Saddam and the Iraqi central leadership went into hiding, as the coalition forces finished occupying the country.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 1 May, Bush declared the "end of major combat operations" in Iraq; this began the occupation phase of the Iraq War, in which coalition forces fought the Iraqi insurgency.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Saddam was captured by U.S. forces on 13 December 2003.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Gulf War began in 1990, and ended in 1991 with a ceasefire between the United Nations coalition and Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The U.S. and its allies tried to keep Saddam Hussein in check with military actions such as Operation Southern Watch, by monitoring and controlling some Iraqi airspace, as well as using economic sanctions.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Violating the Biological Weapons Convention, Iraq's biological weapons (BW) program began in the early 1980s, with help from the U.S. and European countries reportedly unaware of Iraq's intentions.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Details of Iraqi biological and chemical weapons program surfaced after the Gulf War, following investigations by the UN Special Commission (UNSCOM), which had been charged with the post-war disarmament of Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The investigation concluded that the program had not continued after the war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Iraqi military helicopters and planes regularly contested the no-fly zones.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 1998, regime change in Iraq became official U.S. foreign policy with enactment of the Iraq Liberation Act, enacted following the expulsion of UN weapons inspectors months earlier (some had been accused of spying for the U.S.).
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] One month later, the U.S. and UK bombed Iraq during Operation Desert Fox, their rationale being to hamper Iraq's ability to produce chemical, biological, and nuclear weapons, but U.S. intelligence personnel also hoped it would help weaken Saddam's grip on power.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush's inauguration in January 2001, the U.S. moved towards a more aggressive policy toward Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Republican Party's 2000 campaign platform called for the U.S. to "remove" Saddam.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] After leaving the Bush administration, Treasury Secretary Paul O'Neill said that an attack on Iraq had been planned since Bush's inauguration, and that the first U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] National Security Council meeting involved discussion of an invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] O'Neill later backtracked, saying that these discussions were part of a continuation of foreign policy first put into place by the Clinton administration.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Despite the Bush administration's stated interest in invading Iraq, little formal movement towards an invasion occurred until the 11 September attacks (9/11).
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On the morning of 11 September 2001, the al-Qaeda militant organization, led by Osama bin Laden, committed four coordinated terrorist attacks on the U.S., using hijacked commercial airliners to crash into major symbols of American economic and military power.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Messages intercepted by the National Security Agency during the attacks pointed to al-Qaeda's responsibility for them.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] By mid-afternoon, however, Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld ordered the Pentagon to prepare plans for attacking Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to aides near him that day, Rumsfeld messaged: "Best info fast.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Judge whether good enough hit S.H. [Saddam Hussein] at same time.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 12 September, Bush ordered White House counter-terrorism coordinator Richard A.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Clarke to investigate possible Iraqi involvement in 9/11.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Shocked by the sophistication of the attacks, the administration wondered whether a state sponsor was involved.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Clarke's office issued a memo on 18 September that noted wide ideological gaps between Iraq and al-Qaeda, and that only weak anecdotal evidence linked the two.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] However, U.S. vice president Dick Cheney and Rumsfeld expressed skepticism toward's the CIA's intelligence.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] They questioned whether the CIA were competent enough to produce accurate information as the agency underestimated threats and failed to accurately predict events such as the 1979 Iranian Revolution, the 1990 Iraqi invasion of Kuwait, and the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] They instead preferred outside analysis, of which information was supplied by the Iraqi National Congress as well as unvetted pieces of intelligence.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This information alleged that a highly secretive relationship existed between Saddam and al-Qaeda from 1992, specifically through a series of meetings reportedly involving the Iraqi Intelligence Service (IIS).
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The rationale for invading Iraq as a response to 9/11 has been widely questioned, as there was no cooperation between Saddam and al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 20 September 2001, Bush addressed a joint session of Congress (telecast live to the world), and announced his new "war on terror".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This announcement was accompanied by the doctrine of "pre-emptive" military action, later termed the Bush Doctrine.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 21 November, Bush spoke with Rumsfeld and instructed him to conduct a confidential review of OPLAN 1003, the war plan for invading Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Rumsfeld met with General Tommy Franks, the commander of U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Central Command (CENTCOM), on 27 November to go over the plans.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A record of the meeting includes the question "How start?", listing multiple possible justifications for a U.S.–Iraq War.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Some Bush advisers favored an immediate invasion of Iraq, while others advocated building an international coalition and obtaining UN authorization.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush eventually decided to seek UN authorization, while still reserving the option of invading without it.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Also that day, Benjamin Netanyahu testified before the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congress, using expert testimony to encourage an invasion, and stating there was "no question" that Saddam was working on WMDs.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The UK agreed with the U.S. actions, while France and Germany were critical of plans to invade Iraq, arguing instead for continued diplomacy and weapons inspections.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] After considerable debate, the UNSC adopted a compromise resolution, UNSC Resolution 1441, which authorized the resumption of weapons inspections and promised "serious consequences" for non-compliance.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] UNSC members France and Russia made clear that they did not consider these consequences to include the use of force to overthrow the Iraqi government.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Both the U.S. ambassador to the UN, John Negroponte, and the UK ambassador, Jeremy Greenstock, publicly confirmed this reading of the resolution, assuring that Resolution 1441 provided no "automaticity" or "hidden triggers" for an invasion without further consultation of the UNSC.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Resolution 1441 gave Iraq "a final opportunity to comply with its disarmament obligations" and set up inspections by the UN Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC) and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Saddam accepted the resolution on 13 November and inspectors returned to Iraq under the direction of UNMOVIC chairman Hans Blix and IAEA Director-General Mohamed ElBaradei.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As of February 2003, the IAEA "found no evidence or plausible indication of the revival of a nuclear weapons program in Iraq"; the IAEA concluded that certain items which could have been used in nuclear enrichment centrifuges, such as aluminum tubes, were in fact intended for other uses.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] UNMOVIC "did not find evidence of the continuation or resumption" of WMD programs, or significant quantities of proscribed items.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Shortly before the invasion, UNMOVIC stated that it would take "months" to verify Iraqi compliance with resolution 1441.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congress passed the Iraq Resolution, which authorized the President to "use any means necessary" against Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Americans polled in January 2003 widely favored further diplomacy over an invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Later that year, however, Americans began to agree with Bush's plan.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The U.S. government engaged in an elaborate domestic public relations campaign to market the war to its citizens.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Americans overwhelmingly believed Saddam did have WMDs: 85% said so, even though the inspectors had not uncovered those weapons.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Of those who thought Iraq had weapons sequestered somewhere, about half responded that said weapons would not be found in combat.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] By February 2003, 64% of Americans supported taking military action to remove Saddam from power.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In the 2003 State of the Union address, Bush said "we know that Iraq, in the late 1990s, had several mobile biological weapons labs".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Secretary of State Colin Powell addressed the UNSC, continuing U.S. efforts to gain UN authorization for an invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] His presentation contained a computer-generated image of a "mobile biological weapons laboratory".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] However, this information was based on claims of Rafid Ahmed Alwan al-Janabi, codenamed "Curveball", an Iraqi emigrant living in Germany who later admitted that his claims had been false.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Powell falsely alleged that Iraq had ties to al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As a follow-up to the presentation, the U.S., UK, Poland, Italy, Australia, Denmark, Japan, and Spain proposed a resolution authorizing the use of force in Iraq, but Canada, France, Germany, and Russia strongly urged continued diplomacy.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Facing a losing vote as well as a likely veto from France and Russia; the aforementioned countries eventually withdrew their resolution.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Opposition to the invasion coalesced in the worldwide 15 February 2003 anti-war protest that attracted between six and ten million people in more than 800 cities, the largest such protest in human history.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 16 March 2003, Spanish Prime Minister José María Aznar, UK Prime Minister Tony Blair, Bush, and Prime Minister of Portugal José Manuel Durão Barroso as host met in the Azores to discuss the invasion of Iraq and Spain's potential involvement in the war, as well as the beginning of the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This encounter was extremely controversial in Spain, even now remaining a very sensitive point for the Aznar government.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 2004, Madrid suffered the worst terrorist attack in Europe since the Lockerbie bombing, motivated by Spain's decision to participate in the war, prompting some Spaniards to accuse the Prime Minister of being responsible.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In March 2003, the U.S., UK, Poland, Australia, Spain, Denmark preparing for the invasion of Iraq, with a host of public relations and military moves.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In his 17 March address to the nation, Bush demanded that Saddam and his two sons, Uday and Qusay, surrender and leave Iraq, giving them a 48-hour deadline.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The UK House of Commons held a debate on going to war on 18 March where the government motion was approved 412 to 149.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The vote was a key moment in the history of the Blair administration, as the number of government MPs who rebelled against the vote was the greatest since the repeal of the Corn Laws in 1846.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Three government ministers resigned in protest at the war, John Denham, Lord Hunt of Kings Heath, and the then Leader of the House of Commons Robin Cook.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In December 2002, a representative of Iraqi General Tahir Jalil Habbush al-Tikriti, contacted former CIA Counterterrorism Department head Vincent Cannistraro, and stated that Saddam "knew there was a campaign to link him to 11 September and prove he had [WMDs]".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Cannistraro added that "the Iraqis were prepared to satisfy these concerns.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] I reported the conversation to senior levels of the state department and I was told to stand aside and they would handle it." Cannistraro stated that the offers made were all "killed" by the Bush administration because they allowed Saddam to remain in power, an outcome viewed as unacceptable.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] It has been suggested that Saddam was prepared to go into exile if allowed to keep U.S.$1 billion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Egyptian president Hosni Mubarak's national security advisor, Osama El-Baz, sent a message to the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] State Department that the Iraqis wanted to discuss the accusations that the country had WMDs and ties with al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Iraq also attempted to reach the U.S. through the Syrian, French, German, and Russian intelligence services.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In January 2003, Lebanese-American Imad Hage met with U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Department of Defense official Michael Maloof.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Hage, a resident of Beirut, had been recruited by the department to assist in the war on terror.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He reported that Mohammed Nassif, a close aide to Syrian president Bashar al-Assad, had expressed frustrations about the difficulties of Syria contacting the U.S., and had attempted to use him as an intermediary.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Maloof arranged for Hage to meet with Richard Perle, then head of the Defense Policy Board.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In January 2003, Hage met with Iraqi intelligence official Hassan al-Obeidi.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Al-Obeidi told Hage that Baghdad did not understand why they were targeted and that they had no WMDs.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He then made the offer for Washington to send in 2000 FBI agents to confirm this.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He additionally offered petroleum concessions but stopped short of having Saddam give up power, instead suggesting that elections could be held in two years.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Later, al-Obeidi suggested that Hage travel to Baghdad for talks; he accepted.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Later that month, Hage met with General Habbush and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] They also wished to meet with high-ranking U.S. officials.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 19 February, Hage faxed Maloof his report of the trip.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Maloof reports having brought the proposal to Jaymie Duran.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Pentagon denies that either Wolfowitz or Rumsfeld, Duran's bosses, were aware of the plan.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 21 February, Maloof informed Duran in an email that Richard Perle wished to meet with Hage and the Iraqis if the Pentagon would clear it.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Keep this close hold." On 7 March, Perle met with Hage in Knightsbridge, and stated that he wanted to pursue the matter further with people in Washington, D.C.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A few days later, he informed Hage that Washington refused to let him meet with Habbush to discuss the offer (Hage stated that Perle's response was "that the consensus in Washington was it was a no-go").
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Throughout 2002, the Bush administration insisted that removing Saddam from power to restore international peace and security was a major goal.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The principal stated justifications for this policy of "regime change" were that Iraq's continuing production of WMDs and known ties to terrorist organizations, as well as Iraq's continued violations of UNSC resolutions, amounted to a threat to the U.S. and the world community.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush, speaking in October 2002, said that "The stated policy of the United States is regime change. ...
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Bush administration's overall rationale for the invasion of Iraq was presented in detail by Powell to the UNSC.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In September 2002, Blair stated that "Regime change in Iraq would be a wonderful thing.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] That is not the purpose of our action; our purpose is to disarm Iraq of weapons of mass destruction..." In November of that year, Blair further stated that, "So far as our objective, it is disarmament, not regime change – that is our objective.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As Blair made clear in a statement to the House of Commons, "I detest his regime.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] But even now he can save it by complying with the UN's demand.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In September 2002, the Bush administration said attempts by Iraq to acquire thousands of high-strength aluminum tubes pointed to a clandestine program to make enriched uranium for nuclear bombs.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Powell referred to the tubes in his UNSC presentation.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A report released by the Institute for Science and International Security in 2002, however, reported that it was highly unlikely that the tubes could be used to enrich uranium.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Bush administration asserted that the Saddam government had sought to purchase yellowcake uranium from Niger.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 7 March 2003, the U.S. submitted intelligence documents as evidence to the International Atomic Energy Agency.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These documents were dismissed by the IAEA as forgeries, with the concurrence in that judgment of outside experts.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the time, an American official stated that the evidence was submitted to the IAEA without knowledge of its provenance and characterized any mistakes as "more likely due to incompetence not malice".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Since the invasion, the U.S. government statements concerning Iraqi weapons programs and links to al-Qaeda have been discredited, though chemical weapons were found in Iraq during the occupation period.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] While the debate of whether Iraq intended to develop chemical, biological, and nuclear weapons in the future remains open, no WMDs have been found in Iraq since the invasion despite comprehensive inspections lasting more than 18 months.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In Cairo, on 24 February 2001, Powell had predicted as much, saying, "[Saddam] has not developed any significant capability with respect to weapons of mass destruction.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Another justification included the alleged connection between Saddam's and that of terrorist organizations such as al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] While it never made an explicit connection between Iraq and 9/11, the Bush administration repeatedly insinuated a link, thereby creating a false impression for the U.S. public.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Grand jury testimony from al-Qaeda's 1993 World Trade Center bombing trials cited numerous direct connections between the bombers to Hussein's government.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Iraqi National Congress alleged that Saddam had been collaborating with al-Qaeda since 1992 via the Iraqi Intelligence Service (IIS).
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Steven Kull, director of the Program on International Policy Attitudes (PIPA), observed in March 2003 that the administration "has succeeded in creating a sense that there is some connection" between 9/11 and Saddam.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This was after a *New York Times*/CBS poll showed that 45% of Americans believed Saddam was "personally involved" in the attacks.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] And we know that after September 11, Saddam Hussein's regime gleefully celebrated the terrorist attacks on America." The BBC noted the results of a recent poll which suggested that 70% of Americans believe Saddam "was personally involved" in 9/11.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Since the invasion, assertions of operational links between Iraq and al-Qaeda have largely been discredited by the intelligence community, and Powell himself later admitted he had no proof of it.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In October 2002, a few days before the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Powell suggested in his 2003 UN presentation that UAVs were transported out of Iraq and could be launched against the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In actuality, Iraq had no offensive UAV fleet or any capability of putting UAVs on ships.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Iraq's UAV fleet consisted of less than a handful of outdated Czech training drones.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the time, there was a large dispute within the intelligence community whether the CIA's conclusions about the UAV fleet were accurate.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Air Force denied outright that Iraq had any offensive UAV capabilities.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Additional justifications used at various times included Iraqi violation of UN resolutions, the Iraqi government's repression of its citizens, and Iraqi violations of the 1991 ceasefire.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As evidence supporting American and British claims about Iraqi WMDs and links to terrorism weakened, some supporters of the invasion have increasingly shifted their justification to the human rights violations of the Saddam government.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Iraq Resolution of 2002 was passed by Congress with Republicans voting 98% in favor in the Senate, and 97% in favor in the House.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Democrats supported the joint resolution 58% and 39% in the Senate and House respectively.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The resolution asserted the authorization by the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Constitution and Congress for Bush to fight anti-American terrorism.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Citing the Iraq Liberation Act, the resolution reiterated that it should be the policy of the U.S. to depose Saddam's government and promote a democratic replacement.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Armed Forces "as he determines to be necessary and appropriate", to "defend [American] national security ... against the continuing threat posed by Iraq".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The legality of the invasion of Iraq under international law has been challenged since its inception on a number of fronts, and several prominent supporters of the invasion in all the invading states have publicly and privately cast doubt on its legality.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] It has been argued by the U.S. and UK that the invasion was fully legal because authorization was implied by the UNSC.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] International legal experts, including the International Commission of Jurists, a group of 31 leading Canadian law professors, and the U.S.-based Lawyers Committee on Nuclear Policy, have denounced this rationale.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 20 November 2003, *The Guardian* alleged that Richard Perle, a senior member of the administration's Defense Policy Board Advisory Committee, conceded that the invasion was illegal, but still justified.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The UNSC passed nearly 60 resolutions on Iraq and Kuwait since Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Resolution 1441 was most prominent during the run-up to the war and formed the main backdrop for Powell's UNSC address.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the same time, U.S. officials advanced a parallel legal argument using the earlier resolutions, which authorized force in response to Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Under this reasoning, by failing to disarm and submit to weapons inspections, Iraq was in violation of UNSC Resolutions 660 and 678, and the U.S. could legally compel Iraq's compliance through military means.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 2006, Luis Moreno Ocampo, the lead prosecutor for the International Criminal Court, reported that he had received 240 separate communications regarding the legality of the war, many of which concerned British participation in the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congressman Dennis Kucinich announced U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] House Resolution 333 and three articles of impeachment against Cheney.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He charged Cheney with manipulating evidence for Iraqi WMDs, deceiving the public about Iraq's connection to al-Qaeda, and threatening aggression against Iran in violation of the UN Charter.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The original list prepared in March 2003 included 49 members.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Of those 49, only six besides the U.S. contributed troops to the invasion force (the UK, Australia, Poland, Spain, Portugal, and Denmark), and 33 provided some number of troops to support the occupation after the invasion was complete.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Six members have no military, meaning that they withheld troops completely.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Approximately 200,194 troops—148,000 American, 50,000 British, 2,000 Australian, and 194 Polish (GROM special forces)—were sent to Kuwait for the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion force was also supported by Iraqi Kurdish Peshmerga fighters, estimated to number upwards of 70,000.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In the latter stages of the invasion, 620 troops of the Iraqi National Congress opposition group were deployed to southern Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Canada discreetly contributed some military resources towards the campaign, such as personnel from the Royal Canadian Air Force who crewed American planes on missions in Iraq to train with the platforms, and eleven Canadian aircrew who manned AWACS aircraft.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Canadian official Eugene Lang stated that it was "quite possible" that Canadian forces indirectly supported the American operation.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to Lang, Canada's military strongly advocated to be involved in the Iraq War instead of the war in Afghanistan, and Canada mainly decided to keep its assets in the Gulf to maintain good relations with America.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] After the invasion, Canadian Brigadier General Walter Natynczyk served as Deputy Commanding General of the Multi-National Corps in occupied Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Plans to open a second front in the north were severely hampered when Turkey refused the use of its territory for such purposes.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In response to Turkey's decision, the U.S. dropped several thousand paratroopers from the 173rd Airborne Brigade into northern Iraq, a number significantly less than the 15,000-strong 4th Infantry Division that the U.S. originally planned to deploy to the northern front.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The number of personnel in the Iraqi military before the war was uncertain, but it was believed to have been poorly equipped.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The International Institute for Strategic Studies estimated the numbers: the Iraqi Armed Forces at 389,000 (Ground Forces 350,000, Air Force 20,000, Air Defense 17,000, and Navy 2,000), the paramilitary Fedayeen Saddam at 44,000, Republican Guard at 80,000, and reserves at 650,000.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] There were an estimated thirteen infantry divisions, ten mechanized and armored divisions, as well as some special forces units.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Iraqi Air Force and Navy played a negligible role in the conflict.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] During the invasion, foreign volunteers traveled to Iraq from Syria and took part in the fighting, usually commanded by the Fedayeen Saddam.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] It is not known for certain how many foreign fighters fought in Iraq in 2003, however, intelligence officers of the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] First Marine Division estimated that 50% of all Iraqi combatants in central Iraq were foreigners.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In addition, the Kurdish Islamist militant group Ansar al-Islam controlled a small section of northern Iraq in an area outside Saddam's control.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Ansar al-Islam had been fighting against secular Kurdish forces since 2001.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the time of the invasion they fielded about 600 to 800 fighters.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Ansar al-Islam was led by the Jordanian-born militant Abu Musab al-Zarqawi, who would later become an important leader in the Iraqi insurgency.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Ansar al-Islam was driven out of Iraq in late March by a joint American-Kurdish force during Operation Viking Hammer.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In the information, the American forces provided the Dutch Ministry of Defense with the GPS coordinates of the DU rounds, along with a list of targets and numbers fired.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Then, the Dutch Ministry of Defence released the data to Dutch peace group Pax under the Freedom of Information Act.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Coalition forces used 61,000 cluster munitions containing 20 million submunitions during the Gulf War, and 13,000 cluster munitions containing two million submunitions during the 2003 invasion and subsequent insurgency.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Thousands of unexploded munitions from the invasion and previous wars, including cluster munitions, mines and other unexploded ordnance, still posed a threat to civilians as of 2022.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] CIA Special Activities Division (SAD) and MI6 (E Squadron) paramilitary teams entered Iraq in July 2002 before the 2003 invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Once on the ground they prepared for the subsequent arrival of American and British military forces.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Army Special Forces to organize the Kurdish Peshmerga.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This joint team combined to defeat Ansar al-Islam, an ally of Al Qaeda, in a battle in the northeast corner of Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A chemical weapons facility at Sargat was also captured.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Sargat was the only facility of its type discovered in the Iraq war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The U.S. side was carried out by Paramilitary Officers from SAD and the Army's 10th Special Forces Group.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] SAD teams also conducted high-risk special reconnaissance missions behind Iraqi lines to identify senior leadership targets.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These missions led to the initial strikes against Saddam Hussein and his key generals.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Although the initial strikes against Saddam were unsuccessful in killing the dictator or his generals, they were successful in effectively ending the ability to command and control Iraqi forces.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Other strikes against key generals were successful and significantly degraded the command's ability to react to and maneuver against the U.S.-led invasion force coming from the south.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] SAD operations officers were also successful in convincing key Iraqi army officers to surrender their units once the fighting started or not to oppose the invasion force.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] NATO member Turkey refused to allow its territory to be used for the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Army Special Forces joint teams and the Kurdish Peshmerga constituted the entire northern force against government forces during the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Their efforts kept the 5th Corps of the Iraqi army in place to defend against the Kurds rather than moving to contest the coalition force in the south.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Four of these CIA officers were awarded the Intelligence Star for their actions.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] MI6 conducted Operation Mass Appeal which was a campaign to plant stories about Iraq's WMDs in the media and boost support for the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] MI6 also went on to bribe many of Saddam's closest allies to turn over information and intelligence.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to Tommy Franks, "April Fool", an American officer working undercover as a diplomat, was approached by an Iraqi intelligence agent.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] April Fool then sold the Iraqi false "top secret" invasion plans provided by Franks' team.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This deception misled the Iraqi military into deploying major forces in northern and western Iraq in anticipation of attacks by way of Turkey or Jordan, which never took place.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This greatly reduced the defensive capacity in the rest of Iraq, and facilitated the actual attacks via Kuwait and the Persian Gulf in the southeast.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Since the Gulf War, the U.S. and UK had been attacked by Iraqi air defenses while enforcing Iraqi no-fly zones.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These zones, and the attacks to enforce them, were described as illegal by the former UN Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali, and the French foreign minister Hubert Vedrine.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Other countries, notably Russia and China, also condemned the zones as a violation of Iraqi sovereignty.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In mid-2002, the U.S. began more carefully selecting targets in the southern part of the country to disrupt the military command structure in Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A change in enforcement tactics was acknowledged at the time, but it was not made public that this was part of a plan known as Operation Southern Focus.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The amount of ordnance dropped on Iraqi positions by coalition aircraft in 2001 and 2002 was less than in 1999 and 2000 which was during the Clinton administration.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] However, information obtained by the UK Liberal Democrats showed that the UK dropped twice as many bombs on Iraq in the second half of 2002 as they did during the whole of 2001.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The tonnage of UK bombs dropped increased from 0 in March 2002 and 0.3 in April 2002 to between 7 and 14 tons per month in May–August, reaching a pre-war peak of 54.6 tons in September – before the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congress' 11 October authorization of the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The 5 September attacks included a 100+ aircraft attack on the main air defense site in western Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to an editorial in *New Statesman* this was "located at the furthest extreme of the southern no-fly zone, far away from the areas that needed to be patrolled to prevent attacks on the Shias.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Tommy Franks, who commanded the invasion, has since admitted that the bombing was designed to "degrade" Iraqi air defences in the same way as the air attacks that began the Gulf War.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These "spikes of activity" were, in the words of then-British Defence Secretary, Geoff Hoon, designed to 'put pressure on the Iraqi regime' or, as *The Times* reported, to "provoke Saddam Hussein into giving the allies an excuse for war".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In this respect, as provocations designed to start a war, leaked British Foreign Office legal advice concluded that such attacks were illegal under international law.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Another attempt at provoking the war was mentioned in a leaked memo from a meeting between Bush and Blair on 31 January 2003, in which Bush allegedly told Blair that "The U.S. was thinking of flying U2 reconnaissance aircraft with fighter cover over Iraq, painted in UN colours.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] If Saddam fired on them, he would be in breach." On 17 March, Bush gave Saddam 48 hours to leave the country, along with his sons Uday and Qusay, or face war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On the night of 17 March 2003, the majority of B and D squadron British 22nd SAS Regiment, designated as Task Force 14, crossed the border from Jordan to conduct a ground assault on a suspected chemical munitions site at a water-treatment plant in the city of al-Qa'im.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Following their insertion, D squadron established a patrol laager at a remote location outside al-Qa'im and awaited the arrival of B squadron, who had driven overland from Jordan.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Their approach to the plant was compromised, and a firefight developed which ended in one 'pinkie' having to be abandoned and destroyed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Repeated attempts to assault the plant were halted, leading the SAS to call in an air strike which silenced the opposition.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In the early morning of 19 March, U.S. forces abandoned the plan for initial, non-nuclear decapitation strikes against 55 top Iraqi officials, in light of reports that Saddam was visiting Uday and Qusay at Dora Farms, in the Dora farming community in southern Baghdad.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At approximately 04:42 Baghdad time, two F-117 Nighthawk stealth fighters from the 8th Expeditionary Fighter Squadron dropped four enhanced, satellite-guided 2,000-pound GBU-27 'Bunker Busters' on the compound.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] One bomb missed the compound entirely, while the other three impacted the site on the other side of an electrified wall surrounding the main palace building, damaging it and destroying every other structure in the compound.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Saddam was not present, nor were any members of the Iraqi leadership.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Baghdad-area hospitals reported that the attack killed one civilian and injured fourteen others, including four men, nine women and one child.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Later sources indicated that Saddam had not visited the farm since 1995, while others claimed that Saddam *had* been at the compound that morning, but had left before the strike, which Bush had ordered delayed until the 48-hour deadline had expired.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Within seven hours, more than 70 sites were destroyed, effectively depriving the Iraqi military of any early warning of the coming invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] As the sites were eliminated, the first heliborne SOF teams launched from H-5 air base in Jordan, including vehicle-mounted patrols from the British and Australian components transported by the MH-47Ds of the 160th SOAR.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Ground elements of Task Force Dagger, Task Force 20, Task Force 14, and Task Force 64 breached the sand berms along the Iraqi border with Jordan, Saudi Arabia, and Kuwait in the early morning hours and drove into Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Unofficially, the British, Australians, and Task Force 20 had been in Iraq weeks prior.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 20 March at approximately 02:30 UTC, at 05:34 local time, explosions were heard in Baghdad.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Special operations commandos from the CIA's Special Activities Division from the Northern Iraq Liaison Element infiltrated throughout Iraq and called in the early air strikes.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At 03:16 UTC, or 10:16 pm EST, Bush announced that he had ordered an attack against "selected targets of military importance" in Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] When this word was given, the troops on standby crossed the border into Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Before the invasion, many observers had expected a longer campaign of aerial bombing before any ground action, taking as examples the Gulf War or the 2001 invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In practice, U.S. plans envisioned simultaneous air and ground assaults to incapacitate the Iraqi forces quickly which resulted in the shock and awe military campaign attempting to bypass Iraqi military units and cities in most cases.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The assumption was that superior mobility and coordination of coalition forces would allow them to attack the heart of the Iraqi command structure and destroy it in a short time, and that this would minimize civilian deaths and damage to infrastructure.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] It was expected that the elimination of the leadership would lead to the collapse of Iraq's military and government, and that much of the population would support the invaders once the government had been weakened.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Occupation of cities and attacks on peripheral military units were viewed as undesirable distractions.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Following Turkey's decision to deny any official use of its territory, the coalition was forced to modify the planned simultaneous attack from north and south.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Special Operations forces from the CIA and U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army managed to build and lead the Kurdish Peshmerga into an effective force and assault for the North.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The primary bases for the invasion were in Kuwait and other Persian Gulf states.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] One result of this was that one of the divisions intended for the invasion was forced to relocate and was unable to take part in the invasion until well into the war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Iraqis immediately adapted to the invasion, and began using unconventional tactics.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 22 March, American troops first encountered the insurgency tactics that would later define the war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] 1st Class Anthony Broadhead, a platoon sergeant in the Crazy Horse troop of the 3rd Infantry Division's cavalry unit, was in a tank heading towards a bridge in Samawah on the invasion route.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] He waved at a group of Iraqis, but instead of waving back, they began attacking the American tanks with AK-47 rifles, rocket-propelled grenades, and mortars.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Because these types of paramilitary forces were well-armed, but indistinguishable from civilians, they would come to pose a significant challenge for U.S. forces throughout Iraq War.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The invasion itself was swift, leading to the collapse of the Iraqi government and the military of Iraq in about three weeks.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The oil infrastructure of Iraq was rapidly seized and secured with limited damage in that time.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Securing the oil infrastructure was considered of great importance.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Before the invasion, Iraqi forces had mined some 400 oil wells around Basra and the Al-Faw peninsula with explosives.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Coalition troops launched an air and amphibious assault on the Al-Faw peninsula during the closing hours of 19 March to secure the oil fields there; the amphibious assault was supported by warships of the Royal Navy, Polish Navy, and Royal Australian Navy.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 1 April, an F-14 from USS *Kitty Hawk* crashed in southern Iraq reportedly due to engine failure, and a S-3B Viking plunged off the deck of the USS *Constellation* after a malfunction and an AV-8B Harrier jump jet went into the Gulf while it was trying to land on the USS *Nassau*.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The British 3 Commando Brigade, with the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Navy's Special Boat Team 22, Task Unit Two, as well as the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Marine Corps' 15th Marine Expeditionary Unit and the Polish Special Forces unit GROM attached, attacked the port of Umm Qasr.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] There they met with heavy resistance by Iraqi troops.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A total of 14 coalition troops and 30–40 Iraqi troops were killed, and 450 Iraqis taken prisoner.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The British Army's 16 Air Assault Brigade alongside elements of the RAF Regiment also secured the oil fields in southern Iraq in places like Rumaila while the Polish commandos captured offshore oil platforms near the port, preventing their destruction.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Despite the rapid advance of the invasion forces, some 44 oil wells were destroyed and set ablaze by Iraqi explosives or by incidental fire.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] However, the wells were quickly capped and the fires put out, preventing the ecological damage and loss of oil production capacity that had occurred at the end of the Gulf War.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In keeping with the rapid advance plan, the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] 3rd Infantry Division moved westward and then northward through the western desert toward Baghdad, while the 1st Marine Expeditionary Force moved along Highway 1 through the center of the country, and 1 (UK) Armoured Division moved northward through the eastern marshland.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] During the first week of the war, Iraqi forces fired a Scud missile at the American Battlefield Update Assessment center in Camp Doha, Kuwait.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The missile was intercepted and shot down by a Patriot missile seconds before hitting the complex.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Subsequently, two A-10 Warthogs attacked the missile launcher.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Initially, the U.S.' 1st Marine Division fought through the Rumaila oil fields, and moved north to Nasiriyah—a moderate-sized, Shi'ite-dominated city with important strategic significance as a major road junction and its proximity to nearby Tallil Airfield.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] It was also situated near a number of strategically important bridges over the Euphrates River.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The city was defended by a mix of regular Iraqi army units, Ba'ath loyalists, and Fedayeen from both Iraq and abroad.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army 3rd Infantry Division defeated Iraqi forces entrenched in and around the airfield and bypassed the city to the west.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 23 March, a convoy from the 3rd Infantry Division, including the female American soldiers Jessica Lynch, Shoshana Johnson, and Lori Piestewa, was ambushed after taking a wrong turn into the city.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Eleven U.S. soldiers were killed, and seven, including Lynch and Johnson, were captured.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Piestewa died of wounds shortly after capture, while the remaining five prisoners of war were later rescued.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Piestewa, who was from Tuba City, Arizona, and an enrolled member of the Hopi Tribe, was believed to have been the first Native American woman killed in combat in a foreign war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Marines from the 2nd Marine Division entered Nasiriyah in force, facing heavy resistance as they moved to secure two major bridges in the city.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Several marines were killed during a firefight with Fedayeen in the urban fighting.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At the Saddam Canal, another 18 marines were killed in heavy fighting with Iraqi soldiers.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] An Air Force A-10 was involved in a case of friendly fire that resulted in the death of six Marines when it accidentally attacked an American amphibious vehicle.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Two other vehicles were destroyed when a barrage of RPG and small arms fire killed most of the Marines inside.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A Marine from Marine Air Control Group 28 was killed by enemy fire, and two Marine engineers drowned in the Saddam Canal.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The bridges were secured and the Second Marine division set up a perimeter around the city.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On the evening of 24 March, the 2nd Light Armored Reconnaissance Battalion, which was attached to Regimental Combat Team One (RCT-1), pushed through Nasiriyah and established a perimeter 15 km (9.3 miles) north of the city.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Iraqi reinforcements from Kut launched several counterattacks.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Marines managed to repel them using indirect fire and close air support.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The last Iraqi attack was beaten off at dawn.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The battalion estimated that 200–300 Iraqi soldiers were killed, without a single U.S. casualty.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Nasiriyah was declared secure, but attacks by Iraqi Fedayeen continued.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] These attacks were uncoordinated, and resulted in firefights that killed many Fedayeen.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Because of Nasiriyah's strategic position as a road junction, significant gridlock occurred as U.S. forces moving north converged on the city's surrounding highways.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] With the Nasiriyah and Tallil Airfields secured, coalition forces gained an important logistical center in southern Iraq and established FOB/EAF Jalibah, some 10 miles (16 km) outside Nasiriyah.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Additional troops and supplies were soon brought through this forward operating base.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The 101st Airborne Division continued its attack north in support of the 3rd Infantry Division.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] By 28 March, a severe sandstorm slowed the coalition advance as the 3rd Infantry Division halted its northward drive halfway between Najaf and Karbala.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Air operations by helicopters, poised to bring reinforcements from the 101st Airborne, were blocked for three days.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] There was particularly heavy fighting in and around the bridge near the town of Kufl.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Another fierce battle was at Najaf, where U.S. airborne and armored units with British air support fought an intense battle with Iraqi Regulars, Republican Guard units, and paramilitary forces.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] AH-64 Apache helicopter gunships setting out on a mission to attack Republican Guard armored units; while flying low the Apaches came under heavy anti-aircraft, small arms, and RPG fire which heavily damaged many helicopters and shot one down, frustrating the attack.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] They attacked again successfully on 26 March, this time after a pre-mission artillery barrage and with support from F/A-18 Hornet jets, with no gunships lost.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The 1st Brigade Combat Team's air defense battery supported by a COLT (combat observation lasing team) and the Brigade Recon Troop moved in to secure the bridge at Al Kifl late on 24 March.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] When the ADA company was unable to secure the western bank of the bridge the commander called for reinforcements.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Grimsley order LTC Marcone Task Force 3-69 Armor to send a quick reaction force to support the ADA company.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] LTC Marcone sent B 3-7 Infantry to clear and secure the bridge.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Bravo Company was made up of two infantry platoons with M2A2 Bradley Fighting Vehicles and one platoon of M1A2 Abrams tanks.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Bravo 3-7 Infantry secured the bridge and fought for 36 hours through a sandstorm.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] During that time, the soldiers fought against Iraqi Military and Fedayeen forces.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] After 36 hours, B co 3-7 Infantry was relieved on 26 March.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The 101st Airborne Division on 29 March, supported by a battalion from the 1st Armored Division, attacked Iraqi forces in the southern part of the city, near the Imam Ali Mosque and captured Najaf's airfield.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Four Americans were killed by a suicide bomber.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 31 March, the 101st made a reconnaissance-in-force into Najaf.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 1 April, elements of the 70th Armored Regiment launched a "Thunder Run", an armored thrust through Najaf's city center, and, with air support, defeated the Iraqi forces after several days of heavy fighting.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Iraqi port city of Umm Qasr was the first British obstacle.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A joint Polish-British-American force ran into unexpectedly stiff resistance, and it took several days to clear the Iraqi forces out.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Farther north, the British 7 Armoured Brigade, fought their way into Iraq's second-largest city, Basra, on 6 April, coming under constant attack by regulars and Fedayeen, while 3rd Battalion, The Parachute Regiment cleared the 'old quarter' of the city that was inaccessible to vehicles.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Entering Basra was achieved after two weeks of fierce fighting, including a tank battle when the Royal Scots Dragoon Guards destroyed 14 Iraqi tanks on 27 March.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A few members of D Squadron, British SAS, were deployed to southern Iraq to support the coalition advance on Basra.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The team conducted forward route reconnaissance and infiltrated the city and brought in strikes on the Ba'athist loyalist leadership.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Elements of 1 (UK) Armoured Division began to advance north towards U.S. positions around Al Amarah on 9 April.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Pre-existing electrical and water shortages continued throughout the conflict and looting began as Iraqi forces collapsed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] After a rapid initial advance, the first major pause occurred near Karbala.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army elements met resistance from Iraqi troops defending cities and key bridges along the Euphrates River.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] These forces threatened to interdict supply routes as American forces moved north.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Eventually, troops from the 101st Airborne Division of the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army secured the cities of Najaf and Karbala to prevent any Iraqi counterattacks on the 3rd Infantry Division's lines of communication as the division pressed its advance toward Baghdad.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Eleven British soldiers were killed, while 395–515 Iraqi soldiers, irregulars, and Fedayeen were killed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The efforts of the British Army facilitated the re-establishment of the rail lines from the port to Baghdad.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Karbala Gap was a 20–25-mile wide strip of land with the Euphrates River to the east and Lake Razazah to the west.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] This strip of land was recognized by Iraqi commanders as a key approach to Baghdad, and was defended by some of the best units of the Iraqi Republican Guard.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Iraqi high command had originally positioned two Republican Guard divisions blocking the Karbala Gap.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Here these forces suffered heavy coalition air attacks.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] However, the coalition had since the beginning of March been conducting a strategic deception operation to convince the Iraqis that the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] 4th Infantry Division would be mounting a major assault into northern Iraq from Turkey.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] As part of Task Force 20, their formal role was to conduct selected high-priority site exploitation on suspected chemical weapon facilities before heading for the Haditha Dam complex.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Along the way, Delta supported the seizure of H-3 Air Base and also conducted numerous deception operations to confuse the Iraqis as to the disposition of coalition forces in the west.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 18 March 2003, B and D Squadrons of the British 22nd SAS Regiment had now infiltrated Iraq in full strength (D Squadron by air and B Squadron by ground) along with 1 Squadron Australian SASR and headed for H-2 and H-3 Air Base.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] They set up observation posts and called in airstrikes that defeated the Iraqi defenders.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The combined British and Australian Squadrons took H-2 virtually unopposed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] H-3 was secured on 25 March with the assistance of members of Delta Force and by Green Beret ODAs from Bravo company, 1st Battalion 5th SFG; a company of Rangers and Royal Marines from 45 Commando flew from Jordan to the bases and the base was handed over to them.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The SAS teams moved to the next objective – the intersection of the two main highways linking Baghdad with Syria and Jordan, where both squadrons were involved in conducting interdictions of fleeing Iraqi leadership targets heading for Syria.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In northern Iraq in early March, a small reconnaissance team from M Squadron of the British Special Boat Service mounted on Honda ATVs inserted into Iraq from Jordan.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Its first mission was to conduct reconnaissance of an Iraqi air base at al-Sahara.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The team was compromised by an anti-special forces Fedayeen unit and barely escaped thanks to a U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] F-15E that flew air cover for the team and an RAF Chinook that extracted the team from out under the Fedayeen's "noses".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] However the Squadron was compromised by a goat herder; the SBS drove for several days while unknown to them anti-special forces Fedayeen units followed them.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At an overnight position near Mosul, the Fedayeen ambushed the Squadron with DShK heavy machine guns and RPGs, the SBS returned fire and began taking fire from a T-72, the Squadron scattered and escaped the well-constructed trap.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A number of Land Rovers became bogged down in a nearby wadi, so they mined the vehicles and abandoned them – though several did not detonate and were captured and exhibited on Iraqi television.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The SBS was now in three distinct groups: one with several operational Land Rovers was being pursued by the Iraqi hunter force, a second mainly equipped with ATVs was hunkered down and trying to arrange extraction, the third with just 2 operators on an ATV raced for the Syrian border.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The second group was also extracted by an RAF Chinook and the third group made it to Syria and was held there until their release was negotiated, there were no SBS casualties.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Viking Hammer was set to begin on 21 March, however, the ground component of the operation was set back several days owing to the issues around infiltrating most of the 3rd Battalion 10th SFG into Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Islamic Group of Kurdistan surrendered after having suffered 100 men killed in the 21 March strikes.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 28 March, the ground element of Operation Viking Hammer was finally launched with a six-pronged advance, each prong was composed of several ODAs from 3rd Battalion, 10th SFG and upwards of 1,000 Kurdish Peshmerga fighters.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The main advance set off towards Sargat – the location of the suspected chemical and biological weapons site; the force was soon pinned down by DShK heavy machine-gun fire from the surrounding hills.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Navy F/A-18s responded to an urgent CAS request from the force and dropped two 500lb JDAMs on the Ansar al-Islam machine gun nests and strafed the positions with 20 mm cannon before departing due to being low on fuel.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The advance began again only to be halted once more by fire from prepared DShK and PKM machine gun nests, Green Berets from ODA 081 deployed a Mk 19 grenade launcher from the back of a Toyota Tacoma and suppressed the gun positions allowing the Peshmerga to assault and wipe out the terrorists.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After capturing the town of Gulp, the force continued onto the village of Sargat; the village was heavily defended by fortified fighting positions mounting DShKs and mortars along with several BM-21 Grad.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Unable to call in airstrikes due to the close proximity of the Peshmerga, a Green Beret sergeant used a dismounted M2 HMG to suppress the entrenched terrorists, his actions allowed the Peshmerga to bring forward their own 82 mm Mortars and Grads which forced the Ansar al-Islam fighters to retreat.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] To dislodge the terrorists, the Combat Controllers attached to the ODAs vectored in U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Navy F/A-18s which dropped six 500 lb JDAMs that shut down any further resistance.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] With their objectives completed, the 3rd Battalion and their Peshmerga returned to the green line to assist the push on Kirkuk and Mosul.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A specialist SSE team was brought in to document the find at Sargat, the team recovered traces of several chemicals including Ricin along with stocks of NBC protective suits, atropine injectors and Arabic manuals on chemical weapons and IED construction.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Estimates of Ansar al-Islam dead number over 300, many of them foreign fighters, while only 22 Peshmerga fighters were killed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Turkey had officially prohibited any coalition troops from using their bases or airspace, so lead elements of the 10th SFG had to make a detour infiltration; their flight was supposed to take four hours but instead took ten.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 22 March, the majority of 2nd and 3rd Battalions 10th SFG, from Task Force Viking flew from their forward staging area in Constanta, Romania to a location near Irbil aboard six MC-130H Combat Talons.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Several were engaged by Iraqi air defences on the flight into northern Iraq (one was sufficiently damaged enough that it was forced to make an emergency landing at Incirlik Air Base).
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The initial lift had deployed 19 Green Beret ODAs and four ODBs into northern Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Hours after the first of such flights, Turkey did allow the use of its air space and the rest of the 10th SFG infiltrated in.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The preliminary mission was to destroy the base of the Kurdish terrorist group Ansar al-Islam, believed to be linked to al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Concurrent and follow-on missions involved attacking and fixing Iraqi forces in the north, thus preventing their deployment to the southern front and the main effort of the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Eventually Task Force Viking would number 51 ODAs and ODBs alongside some 60,000 Kurdish Peshmerga militia of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK).
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 26 March, the 173rd Airborne Brigade augmented the invasion's northern front by parachuting into northern Iraq onto Bashur Airfield, controlled at the time by elements of 10th SFG and Kurdish peshmerga.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The fall of Kirkuk on 10 April to the 10th SFG, CIA Paramilitary Teams and Kurdish peshmerga precipitated the 173rd's planned assault, preventing the unit's involvement in combat against Iraqi forces during the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Following the Battle of Haditha Dam, Delta Force handed the dam over to the Rangers and headed north to conduct ambushes along the highway above Tikrit, tying up Iraqi forces in the region and attempting to capture fleeing high-value targets trying to escape to Syria.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 2 April, Delta was engaged by half a dozen armed technicals from the same anti-special forces Fedayeen that had previously fought the SBS.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Two Delta operators were wounded (one serious); the squadron requested an urgent aeromedical evacuation and immediate close-air support as a company of truck-borne Iraqi reinforcements arrived.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The DAPs spotted several Iraqi units and engaged them until they were dangerously low on fuel.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Task Force Viking launched an operation to seize the town of Ain Sifni.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The town was strategically important because it straddles the main highway into Mosul.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Once the town fell, it would be clear for the coalition to advance on Mosul.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODAs from the 3rd and 10th SFG called in airstrikes on the Iraqi garrisons in and around the town, causing many of the Iraqi conscripts to flee.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] By 5 April 2003, there appeared to be only two Iraqi platoons left in the town.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 6 April, ODAs 051, 055, and 056 assaulted the town – ODAs 055 and 056 provided fire support along with Peshmerga heavy weapons teams, while ODA 51 made the actual assault on the town.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] As ODA 51 cautiously advanced on the village, it came under intense fire – the two platoons of Iraqis turned out to be closer to battalion strength and equipped with heavy weapons like 82 mm mortars, anti-aircraft guns, and an artillery piece.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After four hours of F/A-18 airstrikes and constant heavy weapons fire from ODA 055 and 056, the assault force entered Ain Sifni; soon afterward, Iraqi infantry counterattacked, supported by several mortars, attempting to retake the town, but it was beaten back by ODA 51 and the Kurds.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 6 April, ODA 391 and ODA 392 from the 3rd SFG and ODA 044 from 10th SFG with about 150 Kurdish fighters were the main force involved in the Battle of Debecka Pass.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 9 April, nine ODAs from FOB 103 encircled Kirkuk after fierce fighting to capture the ridges overlooking the approaches to the city.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The earlier capture of the nearby city of Tuz had largely broken the will of the Iraqi Army and only the Fedayeen remained in Kirkuk.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The first ODA units entered the city the next day; a week later the 173rd Airborne took over responsibility for the city.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After some minor skirmishes the Fedayeen fled.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Staging out of MSS Grizzly, Delta mounted operations to interdict Ba'ath Party HVTs on Highway 1 (Highway 2 and 4 in western Iraq had been secured by British SAS and Australian SAS teams), on 9 April, the combined team seized an airfield near Tikrit.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The 173rd Brigade would eventually take responsibility for Kirkuk days later, becoming involved in the counterinsurgency fight and remain there until redeploying a year later.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 11 April, an advanced element from FOB 102, numbering no more than thirty Green Berets, advanced into Mosul.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The advance had followed several days of heavy airstrikes on three Iraqi divisions defending Mosul.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 13 April, 3rd Battalion 3rd SFG and a battalion from the 10th Mountain Division were ordered to Mosul to relieve the 10th SFG and their Peshmerga allies.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Further reinforcing operations in northern Iraq, the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit (Special Operations Capable), serving as Landing Force Sixth Fleet, deployed in April to Erbil and subsequently Mosul via Marine KC-130 flights.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The 26 MEU (SOC) maintained security of the Mosul airfield and surrounding area until relief by the 101st Airborne Division.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 21 March, ODA 554 of Bravo Company, 2nd Battalion 5th SFG crossed the border with the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] They later rejoined the other half of the team and fought roving bands of Fedayeen.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The ODAs next mission was to work with a CIA-recruited Sheikh and assist British forces in identifying targets around Basra.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The ODA soon established an informant network, they eventually assisted the British in rounding up some 170 Fedayeen in the city; they were eventually replaced by members of G Squadron 22nd SAS Regiment.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Battle of Haditha Dam occurred on 24 March 2003, Rangers from 3rd Battalion, 75th Ranger Regiment, conducted a combat parachute drop onto H-1 Air Base, securing the site as a staging area for operations in the west.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Delta Force recce operators drove through Iraqi lines around the Haditha Dam on customised ATVs, marking targets for coalition airstrikes resulting in the eventual destruction of a large number of Iraqi armoured vehicles and anti aircraft systems.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Delta's reconnaissance of the dam indicated that a larger force would be needed to seize it, so a request was made and approved for a second Delta squadron from Fort Bragg to be dispatched with a further Ranger battalion, along with M1A1 Abrams tanks from C Company, 2nd Battalion 70th Armor.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] C-17 flew the company from Tallil to H-1 and then to MSS (Mission Support Site) Grizzly – a desert strip established by Delta Force located between Haditha and Tikrit; C Squadron, Delta Force was flown directly to MSS Grizzly.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 1 April, C squadron, Delta Force and 3/75th Ranger Regiment conducted a night-time ground assault in their Pinzgauers and GMVs against the Haditha Dam complex.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Three platoons of Rangers seized the dams' administrative buildings with little initial opposition, while a pair of AH-6M Six Guns orbited overhead.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After daybreak, a Ranger sniper shot and killed 3 Iraqis carrying RPGs on the western side of the dam and Rangers on the eastern side engaged a truck carrying infantry, which led to an hour-long contract.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] South of the dam, another Ranger platoon was securing the dam's power station and electricity transformer against sabotage, another platoon was occupied establishing blocking positions on the main road into the dam complex.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The blocking positions came under the sporadic mortar fire, resulting in the AH-6Ms flying multiple gun runs to silence the mortar positions, another mortar team, firing from a small island was engaged and silenced by a Ranger Javelin team.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Rangers captured an Iraqi forward observer dressed as a civilian after sinking his kayak with .50cal fire, the observer had maps of the Rangers positions.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A-10As engaged nearby electricity transformers successfully blacking out the area, but it resulted in a series of explosions and a resulting fire at the stations that dramatically lit the sky – pinpointing the orbiting helicopters for enemy gunmen.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The SEALs conducted a hasty SSE while the Ranger blocking positions received and returned fire, the AH-6Ms and the aerial snipers continued to engage enemy gunmen while the DAPs pushed further out to ensure no reinforcements approached – engaging and destroying numerous Fedayeen armed technicals.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The SSE took longer than expected owing to the size and maze-like structure of the building, the mission completed after 45 minutes, later tests of the material recovered by DEVGRU showed no evidence of chemical or biological weapons at the Objective Beaver.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Bravo and Charlie companies of 1st Battalion 5th SFG crossed the Kuwait border at H-Hour with ODA 531 using breaching demolition charges to clear a path through the sand berms.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Charlie company's seven ODAs in 35 vehicles took the southeastern operation box of the western desert heading towards the towns of Nukyab, Habbariya and Mudyasis, ODA's 534 and 532 split off to head for the area surrounding Nukyab searching for mobile Scud-B TEL launch sites.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 532 also inserted a mobile weather station that provided planners with vital real time weather updates of the battle space.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Bravo company set out for the central town of Ar Rutba and H-3 Air Base with six ODAs and a support ODB (Operational Detachment Bravo).
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODAs 523 and 524 searched a suspected Scud-B storage facility while ODAs 521 and 525 were tasked with clearing several abandoned airfields, with no sign of Scud launchers, ODA 525 deployed a Special Reconnaissance team to conduct pattern of life surveillance on the town of Ar Rutba.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A two-man team called in a pair of nearby F-16C Fighting Falcons to destroy an Iraqi Army radio direction-finding facility they had identified.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 525 attempted to link up with the two-man reconnaissance team and extract it to safety but large numbers of Iraqi vehicles began driving out of the town to them, the ODAs called in immediate air support.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] While waiting, the reconnaissance team and Target Acquisition Marines fired on the Fedayeen leaders with their suppressed MK12 sniper rifle and contacted ODA 521 (who were clearing suspects east of the town) and they reinforced ODA 525.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Over 100 Fedayeen fighters were killed and four armed technicals were destroyed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] To the west ODA 523 reinforced ODA 524, but ran into a pair of armed technicals on the highway, both were destroyed by the GMVs, the Green Berets ceased fire when a civilian station wagon full of Iraqi children drove into the middle of the firefight.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 522 also identified two Fedayeen armed technicals proceeding down the highway toward ODA 523, they set an ambush for them, destroying the vehicles and killing 15 Fedayeen.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The strategic intent of the US Army Special Forces ODAs had been to shut down the main supply routes and deny access around Ar Rutbah and the strategically important H-3 air base, which was defended by a battalion of Iraqi troops and significant numbers of mobile and static anti aircraft guns.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 521 over watching the highway they were travelling on ambushed the convoy destroying a truck mounted ZU-23, the convoy was thrown into disarray, a sandstorm prevented the ODA calling in airstrikes and the convoy scattered into the desert.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Bravo company 5th SFG and the coalition SOF secured the airfield, finding a Roland surface-to-air missile system, around 80 assorted anti aircraft cannon guns including ZSU-23-4 Shilka, SA-7 grail handheld SAMs and an enormous amount of ammunition.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Additionally, ODA 523 discovered what may have been chemical weapons samples in a laboratory on the grounds of H-3.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODAs guided precision airstrikes on Fedayeen anti aircraft guns on the outskirts of the town and on top of the airstrikes, they also struck large groups of Fedayeen militia with Javelin missiles.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 9 April, nine ODAs secured the main roads into the town and commenced a day of near continuous final airstrikes from fix-wing aircraft and Apache helicopters.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Civilians from the town approached the Green Berets asking them to stop the bombing, the Green Berets struck a deal with the civilians and they entered the town the next day.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A B-52 and 2 F-16Cs flew show of force flights over the town as the Green Berets entered, the Fedayeen blended in with the population.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Within days, the Green Berets helped the town to elect a mayor and set up markets, get sixty percent of the electricity grid working and repair water supplies.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 521 and 525 continued to operate in the region, stopping several trucks carrying foreign fighters, they disarmed them, took their details and warned them not to come back before sending them to Syria; in late May, the teams were replaced by the 3rd Armoured Cavalry Regiment.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Army Special Forces (Green Berets) conducted reconnaissance in the cities of Basra, Karbala and various other locations.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After Sargat was taken, Bravo Company, 3rd Battalion, 10th SFG and CIA paramilitary officers along with their Kurdish allies pushed south towards Tikrit and the surrounding towns of Northern Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Previously, during the Battle of the Green Line, Bravo Company, 3/10 with their Kurdish allies pushed back, destroyed, or routed the 13th Iraqi Infantry Division.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Iraq was the largest deployment of the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 563 worked in support of the US Marines around Al Diwaniyah with local Sheikhs and their militias supported by AV-8Bs and F/A-18s; managing to capture the city of Qwam al Hamza.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The following day ODA 563, their local Sheikh and his militia and a small Force Recon team captured the bridge leading to Diwaniyah and the militia attacked Iraqi positions over the bridge, forcing the Iraqi army and Fedayeen to flee toward Baghdad while being harassed by Marine Corps aircraft.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Private first class Jessica Lynch of the 507th Maintenance Company was seriously injured and captured after her convoy was ambushed by Iraqi forces during the Battle of Nasiriyah.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Initial intelligence that led to her rescue was provided by an informant who approached ODA 553 when it was working in Nasiriyah, the intelligence was passed on and Task Force 20 planned a rescue mission.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The plan called for Task Force Tarawa to conduct a deception mission by seizing the bridges across the Euphrates to draw attention away from the hospital Lynch was held at, an airstrike by U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marine AV-8 Harriers would be conducted against one of the bridges to confuse the opposition further and U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marine AH-1W Cobras were tasked to fly over the area to conceal the sound of incoming SOF helicopters.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Air cover was provided by an AC-130 Spectre and a Marine EA-6B Prowler to jam any enemy SAM systems that might be present.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The main assault force of SEALs would arrive by a ground convoy of AGMS Pandur forearmed vehicles and GMV trucks while the hostage rescue element landed directly on the objective in MH-6 Little Birds.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] At 0100 on 1 April 2003, TF Tarawa commenced their deception mission, CIA elements cut the city's power as the helicopters approached their objective, the AH-6s led the way, behind them the MH-6s dropped off Task Force 20 sniper teams at strategic locations around and on the hospital.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The DAPs and the AH-6s covered the MH-60Ks as they dropped off assault teams on the hospital roof and another by the front door, the ground assault convoy arrived and the assaulters raced inside and onto the second floor where Lynch was located.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] 13 minutes later, a MH-60K touched down near the hospital entrance with a team of PJs and SOAR medics on board and transported Lynch to Tallil where it rendezvoused with a standby medical flight and then onto Kuwait, and finally the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Task Force 20 carried out one of the first successful U.S. prisoner of war rescue missions since World War II.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Three weeks into the invasion, the Army's 3rd Infantry Division, with the 1st Marine Division also present, moved into Baghdad.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Units of the Iraqi Special Republican Guard led the defence of the city.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The rest of the defenders were a mixture of Republican Guard units, regular army units, Fedayeen Saddam, and non-Iraqi Arab volunteers.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Initial plans were for coalition units to surround the city and gradually move in, forcing Iraqi armor and ground units to cluster into a central pocket in the city, and then attack with air and artillery forces.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This plan soon became unnecessary, as an initial engagement of armored units south of the city saw most of the Republican Guard's assets destroyed and routes in the southern outskirts of the city occupied.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 5 April, Task Force 1–64 Armor of the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Army's 3rd Infantry Division executed a raid, later called the "Thunder Run", to test remaining Iraqi defenses, with 29 tanks and 14 Bradley armored fighting vehicles advancing to the Baghdad airport.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] They met significant resistance, but were successful in reaching the airport, and eventually secured it after heavy fighting.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The next day, another brigade of the 3rd Infantry Division attacked downtown Baghdad and occupied one of the palaces of Saddam Hussein in fierce fighting.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marines also faced heavy shelling from Iraqi artillery as they attempted to cross a river bridge, but the river crossing was successful.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqis managed to inflict some casualties on the U.S. forces near the airport from defensive positions but suffered severe casualties from air bombardment.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Within hours of the palace seizure and with television coverage of this spreading through Iraq, U.S. forces ordered Iraqi forces within Baghdad to surrender, or the city would face a full-scale assault.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Iraqi government officials had either disappeared or had conceded defeat.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 9 April 2003, Baghdad was formally occupied by coalition forces, and a statue of Saddam was toppled.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Much of Baghdad remained unsecured, however, and fighting continued within the city and its outskirts well into the period of occupation.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Saddam had vanished, and his whereabouts were unknown.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 10 April, a rumor emerged that Saddam Hussein and his top aides were in a mosque complex in the Al Az'Amiyah District of Baghdad.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Three companies of Marines were sent to capture him and came under heavy fire from rocket-propelled grenades, mortars, and assault rifles.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] One Marine was killed and 20 were wounded, but neither Saddam or any of his top aides were found.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S. forces supported by mortars, artillery, and aircraft continued to attack Iraqi forces still loyal to Saddam Hussein and non-Iraqi Arab volunteers.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S. aircraft flying in support were met with Iraqi anti-aircraft fire.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 12 April, by late afternoon, all fighting had ceased.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A total of 34 American soldiers and 2,320 Iraqi fighters were killed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Many Iraqis celebrated the downfall of Saddam by vandalizing the many portraits and statues of him together with other pieces of his cult of personality.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] One widely publicized event was the dramatic toppling of a large statue of Saddam in Baghdad's Firdos Square.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This attracted considerable media coverage at the time.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The fall of Baghdad saw the outbreak of regional, sectarian violence throughout the country, as Iraqi tribes and cities began to fight each other over old grudges.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi cities of Al-Kut and Nasiriyah launched attacks on each other immediately following the fall of Baghdad to establish dominance in the new country, and the U.S.-led coalition quickly found themselves embroiled in a potential civil war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S.-led coalition forces ordered the cities to cease hostilities immediately, explaining that Baghdad would remain the capital of the new Iraqi government.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Nasiriyah responded favorably and quickly backed down; however, Al-Kut placed snipers on the main roadways into town, with orders that invading forces were not to enter the city.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After several minor skirmishes, the snipers were removed, but tensions and violence between regional, city, tribal, and familial groups continued.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Tommy Franks assumed control of Iraq as the supreme commander of the coalition occupation forces.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Shortly after the sudden collapse of the defense of Baghdad, rumors were circulating in Iraq and elsewhere that there had been a deal struck (a "safqua") wherein the U.S.-led coalition had bribed key members of the Iraqi military elite and/or the Ba'ath party itself to stand down.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In May 2003, Franks retired, and confirmed in an interview that the U.S.-led coalition had paid Iraqi military leaders to defect.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The extent of the defections and their effect on the war are unclear.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S.-led coalition troops promptly began searching for the key members of Saddam's government.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] These individuals were identified by a variety of means, most famously through sets of most-wanted Iraqi playing cards.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Later during the military occupation period after the invasion, on 22 July during a raid by the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] 101st Airborne Division and men from Task Force 20, Uday and Qusay Hussein, as well as one of Saddam's grandsons were killed in a massive fire-fight.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Saddam himself was captured on 13 December.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S. special forces had also been involved in the extreme south of Iraq, attempting to occupy key roads to Syria and air bases.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In one case two armored platoons were used to convince Iraqi leadership that an entire armored battalion was entrenched in the west of Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 15 April, U.S. forces took control of Tikrit, the last major outpost in central Iraq, with an attack led by the Marines' Task Force Tripoli.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] About a week later, the Marines were relieved in place by the Army's 4th Infantry Division.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Coalition aircraft flew over 41,000 sorties, of which over 9,000 were tanker sorties.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After the invasion, several factors contributed to the destabilization of Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Paul Bremer issued Coalition Provisional Authority Order Number 2, dissolving the Iraqi Army and other entities of the Ba'athist state.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Ba'athists were excluded from the newly formed Iraqi government.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The first postwar election was won by the United Iraqi Alliance, an electoral coalition composed of mainly Shi’ite groups, which proceeded to ostracize Sunnis.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Shia militia groups pushed Sunnis out of several areas, even emptying entire Sunni neighborhoods in Baghdad during the 2007 troop surge.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The U.S. military established prison camps where disgruntled Iraqis, former Ba'athists, and jihadists met.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi, future leader of the Islamic State, joined al-Qaeda in Iraq (AQI) while detained at Camp Bucca in 2004.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] AQI member Ahmed al-Sharaa, the future leader of al-Nusra Front and Hay'at Tahrir al-Sham, and future Syrian president, was also held there and released in 2008.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] All these factors contributed to Iraq's sectarian violence and the formation and spread of terrorist organizations.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 1 May 2003, Bush gave a speech on the aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln*, announcing the end of major combat operations in the Iraq war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] While he gave the speech, there was a banner hanging behind him that wrote "Mission Accomplished".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The banner, made by White House staff at the request of the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The White House subsequently released a statement that the sign and Bush's visit referred to the initial invasion of Iraq, and disputing the charge of theatrics.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The speech itself noted: "We have difficult work to do in Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] We are bringing order to parts of that country that remain dangerous." Post-invasion Iraq was marked by a long conflict between U.S.-led forces and Iraqi insurgents.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Australia contributed approximately 2,000 Australian Defence Force personnel, including a special forces task group, three warships and 14 F/A-18 Hornet aircraft.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 16 April 2003, Australian special operations forces captured the undefended Al Asad air base west of Baghdad.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The base would later become the second largest coalition facility post-invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Battle of Umm Qasr was the first military confrontation in the Iraq War, with its objective the capture of the port.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Polish GROM troops supported the amphibious assault on Umm Qasr with the British 3 Commando Brigade of the Royal Marines, and the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After the waterway was de-mined by a Detachment from HM-14 and Naval Special Clearance Team ONE of the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Navy and reopened, Umm Qasr played an important role in the shipment of humanitarian supplies to Iraqi civilians.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In Operation TELIC, British troops participated in the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The 1st Armoured Division was deployed to the Persian Gulf and commanded British forces in the area, securing areas in southern Iraq, including the city of Basra during the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A total of 46,000 troops of all the British services were committed to the operation at its start, including some 5,000 Royal Navy and Royal Fleet Auxiliary sailors and 4,000 Royal Marines, 26,000 British Army soldiers, and 8,100 RAF airmen.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The British special forces deployment was codenamed Operation Row and were known as Task Force 7 under Combined Joint Special Operations Task Force-West (Task Force Dagger).
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The U.S.-led coalition forces toppled the government and captured the key cities of a large nation in only 26 days.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The invasion did require a large army build-up like the 1991 Gulf War, but many did not see combat and many were withdrawn after the invasion ended.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This proved to be short-sighted, however, due to the requirement for a much larger force to combat the irregular Iraqi forces in the Iraqi insurgency.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Army Chief of Staff, recommended "several hundred thousand" troops be used to maintain post-war order, but then Rumsfeld—and especially his deputy, civilian Paul Wolfowitz—strongly disagreed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] General Abizaid later said General Shinseki had been right.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi army, armed mainly with older Soviet and Eastern European built equipment, was overall ill-equipped in comparison to the American and British forces.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Attacks on U.S. supply routes by Fedayeen militiamen were repulsed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqis' artillery proved largely ineffective, and they were unable to mobilize their air force to attempt a defense.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi T-72 tanks, the most powerful armored vehicles in the Iraqi army, were both outdated and ill-maintained, and when they were mobilized they were rapidly destroyed, thanks in part to the coalition air supremacy.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Air Force, Marine Corps and Naval Aviation, and RAF operated with impunity throughout the country, pinpointing heavily defended resistance targets and destroying them before ground troops arrived.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The main battle tanks of American and British forces, the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] M1 Abrams and British Challenger 2, functioned well in the rapid advance across the country.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Despite the many RPG attacks by irregular Iraqi forces, few U.S. and UK tanks were lost, and no tank crew-members were killed by hostile fire, although nearly 40 M1 Abrams were damaged in the attacks.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The only tank loss sustained by the British Army was a Challenger 2 of the Queen's Royal Lancers that was hit by another Challenger 2, killing two crew members.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi army suffered from poor morale, even among the elite Republican Guard.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Entire units disbanded into the crowds upon the approach of invading troops, or actually sought out American and British forces to surrender to.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Many Iraqi commanding officers were bribed by the CIA or coerced into surrendering.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The invasion force did not see the entire Iraqi military thrown against it; American and British units had orders to move to and seize objective target points rather than seek to engage Iraqi units.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This resulted in most regular Iraqi military units emerging from the war without having been engaged, and fully intact, especially in southern Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] It is assumed that most units disintegrated to return to their homes.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Estimates on the number of casualties during the invasion in Iraq vary widely.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Estimates on civilian casualties are more variable than those for military personnel.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Approximately 7,500 civilians were killed during the invasion phase.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Project on Defense Alternatives study estimated that 3,200–4,300 civilians died during the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Fedayeen Saddam militia, Republican Guard, and Iraqi security forces were reported to have executed Iraqi soldiers who tried to surrender on multiple occasions, as well as threatening the families of those who refused to fight.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] One such incident was directly observed during the Battle of Debecka Pass.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Many incidents of Fedayeen fighters using human shields were reported from various towns in Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Iraqi Republican Guard units were also reported to be using human shields.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Some reports indicate that the Fedayeen used ambulances to deliver messages and transport fighters into combat.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 31 March, Fedayeen in a Red Crescent-marked ambulance attacked American soldiers outside Nasiriyah, wounding three.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] During the Battle of Basra, British forces of the Black Watch reported that on 28 March, Fedayeen forces opened fire on thousands of civilian refugees fleeing the city.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After the ambush of the 507th Maintenance Company during the Battle of Nasiriyah on 23 March, the bodies of several Americans soldiers who had been killed in the ambush were shown on Iraqi television.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Some of these soldiers had visible gunshot wounds to the head, leading to speculation that they had been executed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Donald Walters, no evidence has since surfaced to support this scenario and it is generally accepted that the soldiers were killed in action.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Five live prisoners of war were also interviewed on the air, a violation of the Third Geneva Convention.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Sergeant Walters was initially reported to have been killed in the ambush after killing several Fedayeen before running out of ammunition.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] However, an eyewitness later reported that he had seen Walters being guarded by several Fedayeen in front of a building.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Forensics work later found Walters' blood in front of the building and blood spatter suggesting he died from two gunshot wounds to the back at close range.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This led the Army to conclude that Walters had been executed after being captured, and he was posthumously awarded the Prisoner of War Medal in 2004.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] It was alleged in the authorized biography of Pfc.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Jessica Lynch that she was raped by her captors after her capture, based on medical reports and the pattern of her injuries, though this is not supported by Lynch.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Mohammed Odeh al-Rehaief, who later helped American forces rescue Lynch, stated that he saw an Iraqi Colonel slap Lynch while she was in her hospital bed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The staff at the hospital where Lynch was held later denied both stories, saying that Lynch was well cared for.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] While Lynch suffers from amnesia due to her injuries, she denied any mistreatment while in captivity.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Also on 23 March, a British Army engineering unit made a wrong turn near the town of Az Zubayr, which was still held by Iraqi forces.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The unit was ambushed and Sapper Luke Allsopp and Staff Sergeant Simon Cullingworth became separated from the rest.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Both were captured and executed by Iraqi irregular forces.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In 2006, a video of Allsopp lying on the ground surrounded by Iraqi irregular forces was discovered.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] During the Battle of Nasiriyah, Iraqi irregulars feigned surrender to approach an American unit securing a bridge.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After getting close to the soldiers, the Iraqis suddenly opened fire, killing 10 soldiers and wounding 40.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In response, American forces reinforced security procedures for dealing with prisoners of war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marine Sergeant Fernando Padilla-Ramirez was reported missing from his supply unit after an ambush north of Nasiriyah on 28 March.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] His body was later dragged through the streets of Ash-Shatrah and hung in the town square, and later taken down and buried by sympathetic locals.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The corpse was discovered by U.S. forces on 10 April.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In 2023, Amnesty International released a report calling for accountability and reparations for human rights violations perpetrated by the coalition during the invasion and subsequent occupation between 2003 and 2011.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] They cited violations of international humanitarian law including secret prisons, torture and other cruel treatment of detainees, indiscriminate attacks that killed and injured civilians, and forced disappearances.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The report stated that both Bush and Rumsfeld had publicly confessed to involvement in secret detentions and faced no criminal accountability.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The report also noted that despite the conclusions of the International Criminal Court in 2020 that British forces had committed war crimes in Iraq, including deliberate killings, rape and torture, no senior British officials have been held criminally accountable.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Massive looting took place in the days following the 2003 invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] According to U.S. officials, the "reality of the situation on the ground" was that hospitals, water plants, and ministries with vital intelligence needed security more than other sites.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] There were only enough U.S. troops on the ground to guard a certain number of the many sites that ideally needed protection, and so, apparently, some "hard choices" were made.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It was reported that The Iraq Museum was among the looted sites.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The director at the time was archaeologist Nawala Al-Mutawalli.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The FBI was soon called into Iraq to track down the stolen items.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It was found that the initial allegations of looting of substantial portions of the collection were heavily exaggerated.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Initial reports asserted a near-total looting of the museum, estimated at upwards of 170,000 inventory lots, or about 501,000 pieces.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The more recent estimate places the number of stolen pieces at around 15,000, and about 10,000 of them probably were taken in an "inside job" before U.S. troops arrived, according to Bogdanos.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Over 5,000 looted items have since been recovered.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] An assertion that U.S. forces did not guard the museum because they were guarding the Ministry of Oil and Ministry of Interior is disputed by investigator Colonel Matthew Bogdanos in his 2005 book *Thieves of Baghdad*.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Bogdanos notes that the Ministry of Oil building was bombed, but the museum complex, which took some fire, was not bombed.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] He also writes that Saddam Hussein's troops set up sniper's nests inside and on top of the museum, and nevertheless U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Marines and soldiers stayed close enough to prevent wholesale looting.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] András Riedlmayer, a specialist in Islamic architecture at Harvard University, said the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] State Department had asked him for advice before the invasion, and that "everybody warned them that the greatest danger was not from Tomahawk missiles but from looting." Keith D.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] More serious for the post-war state of Iraq was the looting of cached weaponry and ordnance which fueled the subsequent insurgency.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] As many as 250,000 tons of explosives were unaccounted for by October 2004.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Defense Department led to delays in the post-invasion assessment and protection of Iraqi nuclear facilities.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Tuwaitha, the Iraqi site most scrutinized by UN inspectors since 1991, was left unguarded and was looted.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Ancient history professor Zainab Bahrani reported that a helicopter landing pad was constructed in the center of the ancient city of Babylon, and "removed layers of archeological earth from the site.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The daily flights of the helicopters rattle the ancient walls and the winds created by their rotors blast sand against the fragile bricks.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] As of 2007, the invasion was the most widely and closely reported war in military history.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Television network coverage was largely pro-war and viewers were six times more likely to see a pro-war source as one who was anti-war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] *The New York Times* ran a number of articles describing Saddam Hussein's attempts to build weapons of mass destruction.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The 8 September 2002 article titled "U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Says Hussein Intensifies Quest for A-Bomb Parts" was later discredited, leading *The New York Times* to issue a public statement admitting it was not as rigorous as it should have been.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] At the start of the war, as many as 775 reporters and photographers were traveling as embedded journalists.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] These reporters signed contracts with the military that limited what they were allowed to report on.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] When asked why the military decided to embed journalists with the troops, Lt.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Marine Corps replied, "Frankly, our job is to win the war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In 2003, a study released by Fairness & Accuracy in Reporting stated the network news disproportionately focused on pro-war sources and left out many anti-war sources.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] According to the study, 64% of total sources supported the war, while total anti-war sources made up 10% of the media (only 3% of U.S. sources were anti-war).
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The study looked only at six American news networks after 20 March for three weeks.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] A September 2003 poll revealed that 70% of Americans believed Saddam was involved in 9/11.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] 80% of Fox News viewers were found to hold at least one such belief about the invasion, compared to 23% of PBS viewers.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Ted Turner, founder of CNN, charged that Rupert Murdoch was using Fox News to advocate an invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Critics argued that this statistic is indicative of misleading coverage by the U.S. media, since viewers in other countries were less likely to have these beliefs.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Independent media also played a prominent role in covering the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The Indymedia network, among many other independent networks including many journalists from the invading countries, provided reports on the Iraq war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In the U.S., the radio program *Democracy Now* was critical of the invasion, and crimes committed by the U.S. in Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The Israeli Military Censor have released gag orders to Fresh and Rotter news platforms preventing them releasing any information about events and action related to the invasion.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Australian war artist George Gittoes collected independent interviews with soldiers while producing his documentary *Soundtrack To War*.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The Iraq War provided the first time in history that military on the front lines were able to provide direct, uncensored reportage themselves, thanks to blogging software and the reach of the internet.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Dozens of such reporting sites, known as soldier blogs or milblogs, were started during the war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] These blogs were more often than not largely pro-war and stated various reasons why the soldiers and Marines felt they were doing the right thing.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] International coverage of the war differed from coverage in the U.S. in a number of ways.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Arab-language news channel Al Jazeera and the German satellite channel Deutsche Welle featured almost twice as much information on the political background of the war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Al Jazeera also showed scenes of civilian casualties and insurgent attacks rarely seen in the U.S. media.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The central U.S. justification for launching the war was that Saddam's alleged development of nuclear and biological weapons and purported ties to al-Qaeda made his regime a "grave and growing" threat to the U.S. and international community.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] During the lead-up to the war and the aftermath of the invasion, critics cast doubt on the evidence supporting this rationale.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] After the build-up of U.S. troops in neighboring states, Saddam welcomed them back and promised complete cooperation with their demands.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Experienced IAEA inspection teams were already back in Iraq and had made some interim reports on its search for various forms of WMD.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Wilson investigated the contention that Iraq had sought uranium for nuclear weapons in Niger and reported that the contention had no substance.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Similarly, alleged links between Iraq and al-Qaeda were called into question during the lead-up to the war, and were discredited by a 2004 report from U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Senator Carl Levin, which was later corroborated by a 2006 report from the Defense Department's inspector general.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] These reports further alleged that Bush administration officials, particularly former undersecretary of defense Douglas J.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Feith, manipulated evidence to support links between al-Qaeda and Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] An FBI agent who interrogated Saddam at this time stated in 2008 that while Iraq may not have possessed WMDs after the 1990s, Saddam likely intended to restart the WMD program if given the opportunity to do so.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] One of the main questions in the lead-up to the war was whether the UNSC would authorize military intervention in Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It became increasingly clear that this authorization would require significant further weapons inspections.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Many criticized their effort as unwise, immoral, and illegal.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Robin Cook, then-leader of the UK House of Commons and a former foreign secretary, resigned from Blair's cabinet in protest over the UK's decision to invade without UN authorization.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Cook said at the time that: "In principle, I believe it is wrong to embark on military action without broad international support.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In practice, I believe it is against Britain's interests to create a precedent for unilateral military action." In addition, senior government legal advisor Elizabeth Wilmshurst resigned, stating her legal opinion that an invasion would be illegal.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan said in September 2004, "[F]rom our point of view, and from the Charter point of view, [the war] was illegal." This drew immediate criticism from the U.S., and was immediately played down.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The most relevant to this issue is Resolution 678".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Criticisms about the evidence used to justify the war notwithstanding, many opponents of military intervention objected, saying that a diplomatic solution would be preferable, and that war should be reserved as a truly last resort.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] (...) Faithful to its values, it wishes resolutely to act with all the members of the international community.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It believes in our ability to build together a better world." The direct opposition between diplomatic solution and military intervention involving France and the U.S. which was personified by Chirac versus Bush, and later Powell versus de Villepin, became a milestone in the U.S.–France relations.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Anti-French propaganda exploiting Francophobic clichés immediately ensued in the U.S. and UK.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] A call for a boycott on French wine was launched in the U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The *New York Post* claimed that France had forgotten the American "sacrifice" in 1944 France.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] On 20 February 2003, British newspaper *The Sun* published a special issue entitled "Chirac is a worm", which said that "Chirac has become the shame of Europe".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] *The Guardian* wrote that both papers expressed the opinion of their owner, Rupert Murdoch.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Both supporters and opponents of the Iraq War widely viewed it within the context of a post–9/11 world, where the U.S. has sought to make terrorism the defining international security paradigm.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Bush often described the war as a "central front in the war on terror".
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Some critics of the war, particularly within the U.S. military community, argued pointedly against the conflation of Iraq and the war on terror, and criticized Bush for losing focus on the more important objective of fighting al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In an October 2002 speech, Retired Marine Gen.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Anthony Zinni, former head of Central Command for U.S. forces in the Middle East and State Department's envoy to the Israeli–Palestinian conflict, called Iraq "maybe six or seven," in terms of U.S.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Middle East priorities, adding that "the affordability line may be drawn around five." However, while commander of CENTCOM, Zinni held a very different opinion concerning the threat posed by Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In testimony before the Senate Armed Services Committee in February 2000, Zinni said: "Iraq remains the most significant near-term threat to U.S. interests in the Persian Gulf region.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Besides arguing that Iraq was not the top strategic priority in the war on terrorism or in the Middle East, critics of the war also suggested that it could potentially destabilize the surrounding region.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Prominent among such critics was Brent Scowcroft, who served as National Security Advisor to George H.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In the opinion of Hayder al-Khoei, Iraq was already "destined for chaos" before 2003.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In a March 2003 Gallup poll, the day after the invasion, 76% of Americans supported the military action against Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In a March YouGov poll, 54% of Britons had approved of military action against Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] By 2007, opposition to the Iraq War had increased to 62% among Americans in a USA Today\Gallup poll.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In 2013, a Gallup poll found that 53 percent of Americans surveyed believed the Iraq War was a mistake.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In 2023, an Axios/Ipsos poll found that 61% of Americans believed the U.S made a wrong decision by invading Iraq.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] This campaign featured a variety of new terminology, much of it initially coined by the U.S. government or military.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The military official name for the invasion was Operation Iraqi Freedom.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Also notable was the usage "death squads" to refer to Fedayeen paramilitary forces.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Iraqi officials were given derogatory nicknames – e.g., "Chemical Ali" (Ali Hassan al-Majid), "Baghdad Bob" or "Comical Ali" (Muhammed Saeed al-Sahaf), and "Mrs.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Anthrax" or "Chemical Sally" (Huda Salih Mahdi Ammash).
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Many slogans and terms coined came to be used by Bush's political opponents, or those opposed to the war.
[src:bbc-news/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Bush's press secretary Ari Fleischer talked about "Operation Iraqi Liberation" in a 2003 press briefing, and "Operation Iraqi Liberation (OIL)" was also used by David Rovics, a popular folk protest singer.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The **2008 Mumbai attacks**, colloquially known as **26/11**, were a coordinated series of twelve Islamic terrorist attacks carried out in Mumbai, Maharashtra, India, from 26 to 29 November 2008, by ten members of the Lashkar-e-Taiba.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A total of 175 people died, including nine of the attackers, and more than 300 were injured.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers arrived in Mumbai via the Arabian Sea.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They departed from Karachi on a Pakistani cargo vessel, hijacked an Indian fishing trawler on the way, and ended their journey to South Mumbai's coastline on inflatable boats.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Eight of the attacks were mass shootings in South Mumbai at Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus, Trident Hotel, Taj Mahal Palace Hotel, Leopold Cafe, Cama Hospital, Nariman House, Metro Big Cinemas, and in a lane behind St.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Xavier's College and the headquarters of *The Times of India*.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In addition to the mass shootings, an explosion occurred at Mazagaon, in Mumbai's port area, and in a taxi at Vile Parle.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] By the early morning of 28 November, all sites except for the Taj Hotel had been secured by the Mumbai Police and security forces.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 29 November, India's National Security Guards conducted Operation Black Tornado to flush out the remaining terrorists; it culminated in the death of the last remaining terrorists at the Taj Hotel and ended the attacks.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Before his execution in 2012, Ajmal Kasab, the sole surviving attacker captured by the Mumbai Police, stated and confessed that the terrorists were members of the Lashkar-e-Taiba and were controlled from Pakistan, corroborating initial claims from the Indian government.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Although initially denying the claims, Pakistan later confirmed that the sole surviving perpetrator of the attacks was a Pakistani citizen.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The capture of Zabiuddin Ansari aka Abu Hamza in July 2012, an Indian national radicalised by Lashkar-e-Taiba, provided further clarity to the plot.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 9 April 2015, the foremost suspected ringleader of the attacks, Zakiur Rehman Lakhvi, was released on bail in Pakistan and disappeared.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] He evaded capture for years, until being arrested again in Lahore on 2 January 2021.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In 2018, former Pakistani prime minister Nawaz Sharif questioned the Pakistani government's allowing men who had committed the attacks to cross into India.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In 2022, one of the masterminds of the attack, Sajid Mir —who the Pakistani government had earlier said was dead — was convicted for funding terrorist activities by an anti-terrorism court in Pakistan and sentenced to 15 years in prison.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attacks strained diplomatic relations between India and Pakistan, and made a huge impact on law enforcement and security officials to deal with such scenarios in the future.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attacks also caused a major political impact on the then ruling government led by the United Progressive Alliance, as the same year, several other cities suffered from Islamic terrorism, which were also perpetrated by Pakistani terror groups.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Many terrorist attacks had occurred in Mumbai since the 13 coordinated bomb explosions that killed 257 people on 12 March 1993.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The 1993 attacks were carried out as revenge for the earlier Bombay riots, in which many Muslims were killed.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Between March 1993 and July 2006 Mumbai city saw 12 notable incidents of bomb attacks resulting in the death of 516 people and injuries to 1952.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Whereas all of these were bomb attacks, the November 2008 Mumbai attacks were *fidayeen* or suicide attacks.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 6 December 2002, a blast in a BEST bus near Ghatkopar station killed two people and injured 28.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The bombing occurred on the 10th anniversary of the demolition of the Babri Mosque in Ayodhya.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A bicycle bomb exploded near the Vile Parle station in Mumbai, killing one person and injuring 25 on 27 January 2003, a day before the visit of the Prime Minister of India Atal Bihari Vajpayee to the city.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 13 March 2003, a day after the 10th anniversary of the 1993 Bombay bombings, a bomb exploded in a train compartment near the Mulund station, killing 10 people and injuring 70.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 28 July 2003, a blast in a BEST bus in Ghatkopar killed 4 people and injured 32.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 25 August 2003, two bombs exploded in South Mumbai, one near the Gateway of India and the other at Zaveri Bazaar in Kalbadevi.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At least 44 people were killed and 150 injured.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On 11 July 2006, seven bombs exploded within 11 minutes on the Suburban Railway in Mumbai, killing 209 people, including 22 foreigners and more than 700 injured.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] According to the Mumbai Police, the bombings were carried out by Lashkar-e-Taiba (LeT) and Students Islamic Movement of India (SIMI).
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A group of men said to number between 24 and 26 received training in marine warfare at a remote camp in mountainous Muzaffarabad in Pakistan.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Part of the training was said to have taken place on the Mangla Dam reservoir in Pakistan.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] From the recruits, 10 were handpicked for the Mumbai mission.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They also received training in swimming and sailing, besides the use of high-end weapons and explosives under the supervision of LeT commanders.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] According to a media report citing an unnamed former Department of Defense official of the US, the intelligence agencies of the US had determined that former officers from Pakistan's Army and Inter-Services Intelligence agency assisted actively and continuously in training.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They were given blueprints of all the four targets – The Taj Mahal Palace Hotel, Oberoi Trident, Nariman House, and Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] After setting sail from Karachi, the terrorists hijacked an Indian fishing boat and killed four people on board.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The boat's captain was kept alive for navigation; he was later killed.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The first events ashore were detailed around 20:30 Indian Standard Time (IST) on 26 November, when 10 men in inflatable speedboats (counts vary) landed at two locations in Colaba.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They reportedly told locals and fishermen (counts vary) who asked them who they were that they were students and to "mind their own business".
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terrorists further split up into groups of two with each going their separate way either on foot or via taxi.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Terminus (CSMT) was attacked by two gunmen, Ismail Khan and Ajmal Kasab.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attack began around 21:30, when the two enter the passenger hall and open fire with AK-47 assault rifles and grenades.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Onsite security personnel are heavily outgunned.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Three are killed confronting the terrorists.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Announcements by a railway announcer, Vishnu Dattaram Zende, alerts passengers to leave the station, which saves many lives.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers kill 58 people and injure 104 others, their assault ending at about 22:45.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] While moving away from the railway station, the attackers pass a police station.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Knowing that they are outgunned against the heavily armed terrorists, the police officers at the station, instead of confronting the terrorists, decide to switch off the lights and secure the gates.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers then head in the direction of Cama Hospital.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Sounds of gunfire alert the hospital staff and they take precautionary measures.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] This includes locking the patient wards, switching off the lights and silencing mobile phones.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terrorists move through the hospital for around 50 minutes.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A police team reaches the hospital and a shootout takes place on the sixth floor.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Two police officers are killed and five are injured including Sadanand Date after which the terrorists leave the hospital complex.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A team of the Mumbai Anti-Terrorist Squad, led by Police Chief Hemant Karkare, search the Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus and then leave in pursuit of Kasab and Khan after receiving a wireless message that Sadanand and his team have been injured in a firefight.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Kasab and Khan open fire on the police vehicle in a lane next to the hospital and receive return fire in response.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Karkare, Vijay Salaskar, Ashok Kamte, and three of their constables are killed.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The only survivor, Constable Arun Jadhav, is severely wounded however he pretends to be dead.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Kasab and Khan seize the police vehicle but later abandon it and seize a passenger car instead.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They then run into a police roadblock, which had been set up after Jadhav radioed for help.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A gun battle then ensues in which Khan is killed and Kasab is wounded.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A police officer, Tukaram Omble, is killed when he tries to disarm Kasab by wrestling his weapon away from him.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] After a physical struggle with other police personnel, Kasab is arrested.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The Leopold Cafe, a popular restaurant and bar on Colaba Causeway in South Mumbai, was one of the first sites to be attacked on 26 November.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Accounts vary with regard to when exactly the attack on Leopold Cafe took place and its duration.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They place the start of the attack between 21:15 and 21:40, while the duration of the attack varies between just over two minutes and 45 minutes.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The two attackers kill 10 people, including some international visitors, and injure many more.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers then head for Taj Mahal Palace Hotel a short distance away.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Two pairs of terrorists hailed taxis to go to their target.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] During these journeys they left time bombs in the vehicles.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The first explosion took place at Wadi Bunder between 22:20 and 22:25.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Three people, including the driver of the taxi, were killed, and about 15 others were injured.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The second one occurred at 22:40 at Vile Parle, killing the driver and a passenger.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A total of 10 bombs were planted during the entire course of events.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In addition, police seized a boat filled with arms and explosives anchored at Mazgaon dock off Mumbai Harbour.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terror attack on the 565 room five star Taj Hotel lasted for 59 hours.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] It began when two terrorists enter the hotel from the front entrance on 26 November at around 21:25 and 22:30.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Before entering the hotel they place an IED at the entrance.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The two terrorists who had attacked Leopold Cafe had by this time had also entered the hotel.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The four terrorists then move through the hotel causing more casualties.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Multiple explosions are reported from the hotel.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] In one instance the terrorists plant a bomb on the fifth floor below the central dome.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Its explosion causes structural damages.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They also start a fire on the sixth floor causing huge plumes of smoke.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Mumbai Police are the first responders, they are soon assisted by the army and navy commandos.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Firefighters rescue 200 hostages from windows using ladders during the first night.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They also incorrectly believed that the Taj Palace and Towers had been cleared of attackers, and soldiers were leading hostages and holed-up guests to safety, and removing bodies of those killed in the attacks.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] However, later news reports indicated that two or three attackers were still in the Taj, with explosions heard and gunfire exchanged.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Fires were also reported at the ground floor of the Taj, with plumes of smoke arising from the first floor.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The final operation at the Taj Palace hotel was completed by the NSG commandos at 08:00 on 29 November, killing three attackers and resulting in the conclusion of the attacks.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Several members of the European Parliament Committee on International Trade were staying at the Taj Hotel when it was attacked, but none were harmed.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] British Conservative Member of the European Parliament (MEP) Sajjad Karim (who was in the lobby when attackers initially opened fire there) and German Social Democrat MEP Erika Mann were hiding in different parts of the building.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Also reported present was Spanish MEP Ignasi Guardans, who was barricaded in a hotel room.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Another British Conservative MEP, Syed Kamall, reported that he along with several other MEPs left the hotel and went to a nearby restaurant shortly before the attack.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Kamall also reported that Polish MEP Jan Masiel was thought to have been sleeping in his hotel room when the attacks started, but eventually left the hotel safely.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Kamall and Guardans reported that a Hungarian MEP's assistant was shot.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Also caught up in the shooting were Indian MP N.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Krishnadas of Kerala and Gulam Noon while having dinner at a restaurant in the Taj Hotel.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Gautam Adani, a billionaire business tycoon of India, was having dinner in the Taj on November 26; he hid in the hotel kitchen and later in the toilet, and came out safely the next morning.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A total of 36 civilians were killed inside Taj Hotel.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Major Sandeep Unnikrishnan of the NSG was fatally shot during the rescue of Commando Sunil Yadav, who was hit in the leg by a bullet during the rescue operations at Taj.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The Oberoi and Trident hotels are a luxury hotel complex having over 800 rooms.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attack started on 26 November between 21:35 and 22:20.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Before entering the hotel, a pair of terrorists placed an IED at the entrance of the hotel.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] After firing at guests in the lobby and in one of the restaurants they placed another IED there as well.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The attackers then moved upwards through the 33 floor Trident Hotel taking hostages as they progressed.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The modus operandi followed was similar to the attack taking place at the Taj.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The first call to the police was at 21:51.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Within minutes police personnel reached the hotel.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] An outer cordon was established and some civilians were rescued.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] While at this stage there was a confrontation between the terrorists and the police, the outgunned police backed away.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Eight marine commandos arrived at around 02:00 on the 27th and engaged the terrorists however heavy gunfire and grenades limited their progress.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] NSG commandos reached the hotel at 07:00 on the 27th.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Rooms were entered using a master key and searched one by one.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] They came across the attackers on reaching the 18th floor of the hotel at 17:30.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Operations continued into the 28th when the attackers were killed at around 15:00.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] During the attack one of the terrorists called up an Indian news channel and the subsequent conversation was aired nationally.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] When reports emerged that attackers were receiving television broadcasts, feeds to the hotels were blocked.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] President of Madrid, Esperanza Aguirre and her accompanying trade delegation were in the hotel premises during the attack.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] 32 hostages were killed at the Oberoi Trident.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Nariman House, a Chabad Lubavitch Jewish centre in Colaba known as the Mumbai Chabad House, run by Gavriel Holtzberg and his wife, was taken over by two attackers on the 26th at around 21:20, and several visiting residents were held hostage.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Police were notified of gunfire in the area around one hour later.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At least 300 locals from adjacent buildings were evacuated and gunfire was exchanged with the attackers.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At around midnight on the 27th, 9 hostages were rescued from the first floor.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] NSG officers did a recce at 15:00 on the 27th.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Attempts are made to ascertain the layout of the interiors of Nariman House.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On the 27th in the morning the Holtzbergs' two year old son had managed to escape with his caregiver.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The three had been taken to a nearby police station.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] By 18:00 NSG had set up an inner cordon and placed its snipers.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] It was getting dark and the NSG had no night vision equipment.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] However at 21:30 electricity to the building was cut and a probe team attempted entry.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A grenade was thrown from inside causing the NSG probe team to withdraw.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At around 22:00 Indian intelligence intercepted a call between the terrorists at Nariman and their handlers regarding killing the hostages.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] NSG was informed about the death of the hostages only after a delay.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The mission had now changed from hostage rescue to seek and destroy.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] During this time more than 60 civilians were shifted from surrounding buildings.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] It was now 01:00 on the 28th when the civilian evacuation was considered complete.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The NSG realised that the police may have initially made an overestimate with regard to the number of terrorists.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terrorists continued firing single shots throughout the night, changing positions as they did so.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] It was decided to enter the building at dawn from the roof.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Commandos were positioned on an adjacent building with a commanding view of the drop off point.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] There were two 84mm Carl Gustav rocket launchers incase the terrorists attacked the helicopter.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Three AK47s were borrowed from Mumbai Police for these commandos.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The gloves for fast-roping could not be found so makeshift gloves had to be made.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At 07:05 the helicopter arrived with 20 commandos with MP5s.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Hundreds of locals and television crews crowded to view the spectacle.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Live telecast of the helicopter and the commandos helped the handlers provide information to the terrorists.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The terrorists prepared themselves on the fourth floor of the five story building by shifting around objects to make makeshift pillbox shaped structures.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The commandos clear the fifth floor, still making sure there were no civilians.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The door to the fourth floor was closed which was breached using an explosive charge.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] The first commando to enter, Gajender Singh Bisht, was shot by a terrorist, and brief gunfire is exchanged.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A grenade thrown by the terrorists injures two commandos.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Retrieving the body of Bisht becomes a priority.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] To this end the officer incharge ordered all surrounding units to fire and tear gas canisters are also thrown in.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] During this firing one of the terrorists was injured.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Intercepted communication between the terrorist and his handler also conveys the same.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] A new entry to the fourth floor was needed.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] At 17:00 on the 28th the explosive creates a hole in a wall, stunning the terrorists.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] Commandos enter the room and after a momentary gunfight the two terrorists were killed with no more loss of life to the NSG.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] On the second floor more hostages were found dead.
[src:bbc-news/2008-mumbai-attacks-p01] David Kilcullen writes that the Holtzbergs' had been "horrifically tortured".
